	<item>
		<title>San Francisco, Oakland, Fremont, CA</title>
		<link>http://telelanguage.com/san-francisco-oakland-fremont-ca/</link>
		<pubDate>Mon, 14 Nov 2016 12:32:36 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://telelanguage.com/?page_id=2829</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[[vc_row][vc_column width="2/3"][vc_column_text]<b>Telelanguage has been providing our customers with the </b><b>highest quality language services </b><b>since 1991 in San Francisco, Oakland, Fremont, CA. </b>We are a reliable and innovative leader in the language industry. We provide <a href="http://telelanguage.com/services/" target="_blank" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?hl=en&amp;q=http://telelanguage.com/services/&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1481137910714000&amp;usg=AFQjCNEjQpRzw7DKb6b4EoWeWg4rPvW-Dw">interpretation and translation services</a> to over 1,400 organizations throughout the United States – <a href="http://telelanguage.com/industries/" target="_blank" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?hl=en&amp;q=http://telelanguage.com/industries/&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1481137910714000&amp;usg=AFQjCNGCsGYOKix_KYAT6FCYvi1wgVq5Ig">across all industries</a>.

<b>Immigrant Population</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">: 1,245,521 </span>

<b>Percent of Population</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">: 29.50% </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Source: </span><a href="http://www.thedailybeast.com/galleries/2010/07/27/20-u-s-cities-with-the-most-immigrants.html" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">The Daily Beast</span></a>

<b>San Francisco </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">(SF), officially the City and County of San Francisco, is the cultural, commercial, and financial center of Northern California and the only consolidated city-county in California. San Francisco is about 46.9 square miles in area. It is located on the north end of the San Francisco Peninsula. It is the smallest county in the state.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">The California Gold Rush of 1849 brought rapid growth, making it the largest city on the West Coast at the time.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">San Francisco has a minority-majority population, as non-Hispanic whites comprise less than half of the population, 41.9%, down from 92.5% in 1940. As of the 2010 census, the ethnic makeup and population of San Francisco included: 390,387 Whites (48%), 267,915 Asians (33%), 48,870 African Americans (6%), and others. There were 121,744 Hispanics or Latinos of any race (15%).</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">In 2010, residents of Chinese ethnicity constituted the largest single ethnic minority group in San Francisco at 21% of the population; the other Asian groups are Filipinos (5%) and Vietnamese (2%). The population of Chinese ancestry is most heavily concentrated in Chinatown, Sunset District, and Richmond District, whereas Filipinos are most concentrated in the Crocker-Amazon (which is contiguous with the Filipino community of Daly City, which has one of the highest concentrations of Filipinos in North America), as well as in SoMa. The Tenderloin District is home to a large portion of the city's Vietnamese population as well as businesses and restaurants, which is known as the city's Little Saigon.</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">The principal Hispanic groups in the city were those of Mexican (7%) and Salvadoran (2%) ancestry. The Hispanic population is most heavily concentrated in the Mission District, Tenderloin District, and Excelsior District. The city's percentage of Hispanic residents is less than half of that of the state.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Source: </span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/San_Francisco" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/San_Francisco</span></a>

<b>Oakland </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">is the largest city and the county seat of Alameda County, California, United States. A major West Coast port city, Oakland is the largest city in the East Bay region of the San Francisco Bay Area, the third largest city overall in the San Francisco Bay Area, the eighth largest city in California, and the 45th largest city in the United States, with a population of 419,267 as of 2015. It serves as a trade center for the San Francisco Bay Area; its Port of Oakland is the busiest port in the San Francisco Bay, the entirety of Northern California, and the fifth busiest in the United States.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Oakland is known for its sustainability practices, including a top ranking for usage of electricity from renewable resources. Oakland is also known for its history of political activism, as well as its professional sports franchises and major corporations, which include health care, dot-com companies, and manufacturers of household products. In addition, due to a steady influx of immigrants during the 20th century, along with thousands of African-American war-industry workers who relocated from the Deep South during the 1940s, Oakland is the most ethnically diverse major city in the country.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Source: </span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oakland,_California" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oakland,_California</span></a>

<b>Fremont</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> is</span> <span style="font-weight: 400;">located in the southeast section of the San Francisco Bay Area in the East Bay region primarily, Fremont has a population of around 230,000. It is the fourth most populous city in the San Francisco Bay Area, and the largest suburb in the metropolis.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Fremont is home to the largest population of Afghan Americans in the United States.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Mission San Jose has the highest concentration of Asian Americans in Fremont – over 50% of the population as of the 2000 census. </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">As of 2010 more than half the residents of Fremont were of Asian ancestry, with large populations of Chinese, Asian Indians, and Filipinos.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Source: </span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fremont,_California" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fremont,_California</span></a>[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][vc_column width="1/3"][vc_column_text][awesome-weather location='San Francisco Oakland Fremont CA' custom_bg_color='#78569F'][/vc_column_text][vc_widget_sidebar title="Other Industries" sidebar_id="shop"][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row el_class="parallax-section forms-rows" css=".vc_custom_1479126621357{margin-top: 50px !important;background-color: #373d67 !important;}"][vc_column][contact-form-7 id="1554"][/vc_column][/vc_row]]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>New York, Northern New Jersey, Long Island, NY. NJ. PA.</title>
		<link>http://telelanguage.com/new-york-northern-new-jersey-long-island-ny-nj-pa/</link>
		<pubDate>Mon, 14 Nov 2016 12:33:10 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://telelanguage.com/?page_id=2833</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[[vc_row][vc_column width="2/3"][vc_column_text]<b>Telelanguage has been providing our customers with the </b><b>highest quality language services </b><b>since 1991 in New York, Northern New Jersey, Long Island, NY. NJ. PA. </b>We are a reliable and innovative leader in the language industry. We provide <a href="http://telelanguage.com/services/" target="_blank" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?hl=en&amp;q=http://telelanguage.com/services/&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1481137910714000&amp;usg=AFQjCNEjQpRzw7DKb6b4EoWeWg4rPvW-Dw">interpretation and translation services</a> to over 1,400 organizations throughout the United States – <a href="http://telelanguage.com/industries/" target="_blank" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?hl=en&amp;q=http://telelanguage.com/industries/&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1481137910714000&amp;usg=AFQjCNGCsGYOKix_KYAT6FCYvi1wgVq5Ig">across all industries</a>.

<b>Immigrant Population</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">: 5,317,616 </span>

<b>Percent of Population</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">: 28.10% </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">There is no more famous city for immigrants in America, and maybe even the world, than New York City. The Statue of Liberty has long been a beacon of the city’s welcoming attitude toward foreigners.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Source: </span><a href="http://www.thedailybeast.com/galleries/2010/07/27/20-u-s-cities-with-the-most-immigrants.html" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">The Daily Beast</span></a>

<b>New York</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">...The City of New York, often called New York City or simply New York, is the most populous city in the United States.[9] Located at the southern tip of the state of New York, the city is the center of the New York metropolitan area, one of the most populous urban agglomerations in the world.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Home to the headquarters of the United Nations, New York is an important center for international diplomacy and has been described as the cultural and financial capital of the world.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">The city and its metropolitan area constitute the premier gateway for legal immigration to the United States, and as many as 800 languages are spoken in New York, making it the most linguistically diverse city in the world.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Approximately 37% of the city's population is foreign born. In New York, no single country or region of origin dominates. The ten largest sources of foreign-born individuals in the city as of 2011 were the Dominican Republic, China, Mexico, Guyana, Jamaica, Ecuador, Haiti, India, Russia, and Trinidad and Tobago, while the Bangladeshi immigrant population has since become one of the fastest growing in the city, counting over 74,000 by 2013.</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Asian Americans in New York City, according to the 2010 Census, number more than one million, greater than the combined totals of San Francisco and Los Angeles. New York contains the highest total Asian population of any U.S. city proper. The New York City borough of Queens is home to the state's largest Asian American population and the largest Andean (Colombian, Ecuadorian, Peruvian, and Bolivian) populations in the United States, and is also the most ethnically diverse urban area in the world.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Source:  </span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_York_City" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_York_City</span></a>

<b>New Jersey</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">...Jersey City is the second most populous city in the U.S. state of New Jersey after Newark. It is the seat of Hudson County as well as the county's largest city.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Jersey City is one of the most ethnically diverse cities in the world. The city is a major port of entry for immigration to the United States and a major employment center at the approximate core of the New York City metropolitan region; and given its proximity to Manhattan, Jersey City has evolved a globally cosmopolitan ambiance of its own, demonstrating a robust and growing demographic and cultural diversity with respect to metrics including nationality, religion, race, and domiciliary partnership.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">There were an estimated 68,857 Hispanic Americans in Jersey City, 27.4% of the population, according to the 2013 American Community Survey. </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Immigrants from South America, led by Ecuador, are a growing component of Jersey City's population, Puerto Rican Americans constitute the largest Hispanic group in Jersey City.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">There were an estimated 60,922 Asian Americans in Jersey City, according to the 2013 American Community Survey.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">India Square, also known as "Little India" or "Little Bombay", home to the highest concentration of Asian Indians in the Western Hemisphere, is a rapidly growing Indian American ethnic enclave in Jersey City. Indian Americans constituted 10.9% of the overall population of Jersey City in 2010, the highest proportion of any major U.S. city.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Filipino people make up 7% of Jersey City's population. The Five Corners district is home to a thriving Filipino community and Jersey City's Little Manila, which is the second-largest Asian American subgroup in the city.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Arab Americans numbered an estimated 14,518 individuals in Hudson County as per the 2012 American Community Survey, representing 2.3% of the county's total population. Arab Americans are most concentrated in Jersey City, led by Egyptian Americans, including the largest population of Coptic Christians in the United States. There is a notable Moroccan American population in Jersey City.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Source: </span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jersey_City,_New_Jersey" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jersey_City,_New_Jersey</span></a>

<b>Long Island </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">(L.I.C.) is the westernmost residential and commercial neighborhood of the New York City borough of Queens. L.I.C. is noted for its rapid and ongoing residential growth and gentrification, its waterfront parks, and its thriving arts community.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">The number of Hispanics and Asians all grew, according to a United States survey in 2013. Asians, in particular, increased in number last year, expanding by 6%, and  Hispanics and Latinos grew by 2%. </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Source: </span>

<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Long_Island_City" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Long_Island_City</span></a>

<a href="http://www.longislandindex.org/data_posts/long-islands-changing-population/" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">http://www.longislandindex.org/data_posts/long-islands-changing-population/</span></a>[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][vc_column width="1/3"][vc_column_text][awesome-weather location='New York Northern New Jersey Long Island NY NJ PA' custom_bg_color='#78569F'][/vc_column_text][vc_widget_sidebar title="Other Industries" sidebar_id="shop"][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row el_class="parallax-section forms-rows" css=".vc_custom_1479126621357{margin-top: 50px !important;background-color: #373d67 !important;}"][vc_column][contact-form-7 id="1554"][/vc_column][/vc_row]]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>Chicago, Naperville, Joliet, IL. IN. WI.</title>
		<link>http://telelanguage.com/chicago-naperville-joliet-il-in-wi/</link>
		<pubDate>Mon, 14 Nov 2016 12:33:41 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://telelanguage.com/?page_id=2834</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[[vc_row][vc_column width="2/3"][vc_column_text]<b>Telelanguage has been providing our customers with the </b><b>highest quality language services </b><b>since 1991 in Chicago, Naperville, Joliet, IL. IN. WI. </b>We are a reliable and innovative leader in the language industry. We provide <a href="http://telelanguage.com/services/" target="_blank" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?hl=en&amp;q=http://telelanguage.com/services/&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1481137910714000&amp;usg=AFQjCNEjQpRzw7DKb6b4EoWeWg4rPvW-Dw">interpretation and translation services</a> to over 1,400 organizations throughout the United States – <a href="http://telelanguage.com/industries/" target="_blank" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?hl=en&amp;q=http://telelanguage.com/industries/&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1481137910714000&amp;usg=AFQjCNGCsGYOKix_KYAT6FCYvi1wgVq5Ig">across all industries</a>.

<b>Immigrant Population</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">: 1,675,949 </span>

<b>Percent of Population</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">: 17.64% </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Chicago began growing as an immigrant city in the 1880s, with large numbers of Polish, German, and Eastern Europeans </span><a href="http://encyclopedia.chicagohistory.org/pages/962.html" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">migrating there in large numbers.</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Since then, the city has become home to people originally from Mexico, the Caribbean, Latin America, and Asia.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Source: </span><a href="http://www.thedailybeast.com/galleries/2010/07/27/20-u-s-cities-with-the-most-immigrants.html" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">The Daily Beast</span></a>

<b>Chicago, </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">officially the City of Chicago, is the third-most populous city in the United States. With over 2.7 million residents, it is the most populous city in the state of Illinois and the Midwestern United States, and the county seat of Cook County. The Chicago metropolitan area, often referred to as Chicagoland, has nearly 10 million people and is the third-largest in the U.S.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">From the last two decades of the 19th century, Chicago was the destination of waves of immigrants from Ireland, Southern, Central and Eastern Europe, including Italians, Jews, Poles, Lithuanians, Serbs and Czechs.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Chicago has a Hispanic or Latino population of 28.9%. (Its members may belong to any race; 21.4% Mexican, 3.8% Puerto Rican, 0.7% Guatemalan, 0.6% Ecuadorian, 0.3% Cuban, 0.3% Colombian, 0.2% Honduran, 0.2% Salvadoran, 0.2% Peruvian)</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">According to the 2008–2012 American Community Survey, the ancestral groups having 10,000 or more persons in Chicago were:[137]</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Irish: (137,799)</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Polish: (134,032)</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">German: (120,328)</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Italian: (77,967)</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">American: (37,118)</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">English: (36,145)</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">African American: (32,727)</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Russian: (19,771)</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Arab: (17,598)</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">European: (15,753)</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Swedish: (15,151)</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Greek: (15,129)</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">French (except Basque): (11,410)</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Ukrainian: (11,104)</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">West Indian (except Hispanic groups): (10,349)</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Persons identifying themselves as "Other groups" were classified at 1.72 million, and unclassified or not reported were approximately 153,000.[137]</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Source: </span>

<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chicago" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chicago</span></a>

<a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20140904195603/http://factfinder2.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?src=CF" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">https://web.archive.org/web/20140904195603/http://factfinder2.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?src=CF</span></a>

<b>Naperville </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">is a city in DuPage and Will counties in the U.S. state of Illinois, and a suburb of Chicago. Naperville was voted the second-best place to live in the United States by Money magazine in 2006. It was rated 1st on the list of best cities for early retirement in 2013 by Kiplinger. In a 2010 study, Naperville was named the wealthiest city in the Midwest and eleventh in the nation with a population over 75,000.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">In 2011, 14.9% of Naperville's residents were Asian, making it the Chicago suburb with the tenth highest percentage of Asians.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Source: </span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Naperville,_Illinois" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Naperville,_Illinois</span></a>

<b>Joliet </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">is a city in Kendall and Will counties in the U.S. state of Illinois, 40 miles (64 km) southwest of Chicago. It is the county seat of Will County. At the 2010 census, the city was the fourth largest in Illinois, with a population of 147,433. </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Source: </span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joliet,_Illinois" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joliet,_Illinois</span></a>[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][vc_column width="1/3"][vc_column_text][awesome-weather location='Chicago Naperville Joliet IL IN WI' custom_bg_color='#78569F'][/vc_column_text][vc_widget_sidebar title="Other Industries" sidebar_id="shop"][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row el_class="parallax-section forms-rows" css=".vc_custom_1479126621357{margin-top: 50px !important;background-color: #373d67 !important;}"][vc_column][contact-form-7 id="1554"][/vc_column][/vc_row]]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>Washington, Arlington, Alexandria, DC. VA.</title>
		<link>http://telelanguage.com/washington-arlington-alexandria-dc-va/</link>
		<pubDate>Mon, 14 Nov 2016 12:34:06 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://telelanguage.com/?page_id=2836</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[[vc_row][vc_column width="2/3"][vc_column_text]<b>Telelanguage has been providing our customers with the </b><b>highest quality language services </b><b>since 1991 in Washington, Arlington, Alexandria, DC. VA. </b>We are a reliable and innovative leader in the language industry. We provide <a href="http://telelanguage.com/services/" target="_blank" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?hl=en&amp;q=http://telelanguage.com/services/&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1481138528295000&amp;usg=AFQjCNETQHH-PS-MUhGRsy0Y2DLUwaU1gw">interpretation and translation services</a> to over 1,400 organizations throughout the United States – <a href="http://telelanguage.com/industries/" target="_blank" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?hl=en&amp;q=http://telelanguage.com/industries/&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1481138528295000&amp;usg=AFQjCNEDWAaQPIufGCrnPCRM3TTenBHXAg">across all industries</a>.

<b>Immigrant Population</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">: 1,073,591 </span>

<b>Percent of Population</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">: 20.23% </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Washington D.C. rose as a hub for immigrants after the 1970s, with the foreign-born population of the city </span><a href="http://www.brookings.edu/~/media/Files/rc/reports/2001/04_washington_dc_singer/immigration.pdf" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">reaching</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> 800,000 in 1998. The city is home to people originally from El Salvador, Vietnam, India, the Philippines and Ethiopia.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Source: </span><a href="http://www.thedailybeast.com/galleries/2010/07/27/20-u-s-cities-with-the-most-immigrants.html" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">The Daily Beast</span></a>

<b>Washington D.C.</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">, formally the District of Columbia and commonly referred to as "Washington", "the District", or simply "D.C.", is the capital of the United States.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Washington had an estimated population of 672,228 as of July 2015. Commuters from the surrounding Maryland and Virginia suburbs raise the city's population to more than one million during the workweek. The Washington metropolitan area, of which the District is a part, has a population of over 6 million, the sixth-largest metropolitan statistical area in the country.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">According to a 2009 Census, the percentage of foreign-born persons in Washington D.C. was 12%, ranking it 60th in the United States for foreign-born populations.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Source: </span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Washington,_D.C" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Washington,_D.C</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">.</span>

<b>Arlington County </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">is a county in the Commonwealth of Virginia. It is coterminous with the U.S. Census Bureau-census-designated place of Arlington, which is the second-largest principal city of the Washington metropolitan area.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">A 2012 Census found Arlington County to have 9.9% Non-Hispanic Asian (2.0% Indian, 1.7% Chinese, 1.1% Filipino, 0.9% Korean, 0.7% Vietnamese, 2.7% Other Asian), and </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">15.4% of the population was Hispanic or Latino of any race (3.4% Salvadoran, 2.0% Bolivian, 1.7% Mexican, 1.5% Guatemalan, 0.8% Puerto Rican, 0.7% Peruvian, 0.6% Colombian)</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">According to a 2009 Census, the percentage of foreign-born persons in Arlington, Virginia was 21.8%, ranking it 33rd in the United States for foreign-born populations.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Source: </span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arlington_County,_Virginia" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arlington_County,_Virginia</span></a>

<b>Alexandria</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> is an independent city in the United States Commonwealth of Virginia. As of the 2010 census, the population was 139,966, and in 2015, the population was estimated to be 153,511. </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">According to a 2010 Census, 16.1% of the population were Hispanics or Latinos of any national origin (4.6% Salvadoran, 1.7% Mexican, 1.6% Honduran, 1.1% Guatemalan, 1.1% Puerto Rican, 0.9% Bolivian, 0.8% Peruvian, 0.4% Colombian), and 6.0% Asian (1.3% Indian, 1.0% Filipino, 0.9% Chinese, 0.8% Korean, 0.5% Thai, 0.3% Vietnamese, 0.2% Japanese, 1.0% Other).</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Source: </span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alexandria,_Virginia" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alexandria,_Virginia</span></a>[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][vc_column width="1/3"][vc_column_text][awesome-weather location='Washington Arlington Alexandria DC VA' custom_bg_color='#78569F'][/vc_column_text][vc_widget_sidebar title="Other Industries" sidebar_id="shop"][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row el_class="parallax-section forms-rows" css=".vc_custom_1479126621357{margin-top: 50px !important;background-color: #373d67 !important;}"][vc_column][contact-form-7 id="1554"][/vc_column][/vc_row]]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>Dallas, Fort Worth, Arlington, TX</title>
		<link>http://telelanguage.com/dallas-fort-worth-arlington-tx/</link>
		<pubDate>Mon, 14 Nov 2016 12:34:28 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://telelanguage.com/?page_id=2838</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[[vc_row][vc_column width="2/3"][vc_column_text]<b>Telelanguage has been providing our customers with the </b><b>highest quality language services </b><b>since 1991 in Dallas, Fort Worth, Arlington, TX. </b>We are a reliable and innovative leader in the language industry. We provide <a href="http://telelanguage.com/services/" target="_blank" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?hl=en&amp;q=http://telelanguage.com/services/&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1481138528295000&amp;usg=AFQjCNETQHH-PS-MUhGRsy0Y2DLUwaU1gw">interpretation and translation services</a> to over 1,400 organizations throughout the United States – <a href="http://telelanguage.com/industries/" target="_blank" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?hl=en&amp;q=http://telelanguage.com/industries/&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1481138528295000&amp;usg=AFQjCNEDWAaQPIufGCrnPCRM3TTenBHXAg">across all industries</a>.

<b>Immigrant Population</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">: 1,090,385 </span>

<b>Percent of Population</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">: 17.73% </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Given Dallas’ proximity to the Mexican border, the city has long attracted many immigrants. The city's second-largest immigrant group comes from Vietnam. The city also has large numbers of people from El Salvador, India, China, and Russia.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Source: </span><a href="http://www.thedailybeast.com/galleries/2010/07/27/20-u-s-cities-with-the-most-immigrants.html" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">The Daily Beast</span></a>

<b>Dallas</b> <span style="font-weight: 400;">is a major city in the state of Texas and is the largest urban center of the fourth most populous metropolitan area in the United States. The city proper ranks </span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_United_States_cities_by_population" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">ninth in the U.S.</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> and third in Texas after Houston and San Antonio.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Located in North Texas, Dallas is the main core of the largest metropolitan area in the South and the largest inland metropolitan area in the United States that lacks any navigable link to the sea.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">In addition, recent data showed that 26.5% of Dallas' population and 17% of residents in the Metroplex as a whole were foreign-born.</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Dallas is a major destination for Mexican immigrants.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">In addition, Dallas and its suburbs are home to a large number of Asian residents including those of Indian, Vietnamese, Chinese, Korean, Filipino, Japanese, and other heritage.There are also a significant number of people from the Horn of Africa, immigrants from Ethiopia, Eritrea, and Somalia. With so many immigrant groups, there are often multilingual signs in the linguistic landscape.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">The Dallas-Fort-Worth Metroplex has an estimated 70,000 Russian-speakers, mostly immigrants from the former Soviet Bloc. Included in this population are Russians, Russian Jews, Ukrainians, Belorussians, Moldavians, Uzbek, Kirghiz, and others. The Russian-speaking population of Dallas has continued to grow</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Source: </span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dallas" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dallas</span></a>

<b>Fort Worth </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">is the 16th-largest city in the United States and the fifth-largest city in the state of Texas.. According to the 2015 census, estimates, Fort Worth's population is 833,319. </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">The July 2004 census estimates have placed Fort Worth in the top 20 most populous cities (# 19) in the U.S. with the population at 604,538.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">From a 2000 Census, </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">About 29.81% of the population were Hispanics or Latinos of any race. The percentage of foreign-born citizens (from a 2009 Census) was 17.9% of the population.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Source: </span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fort_Worth,_Texas" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fort_Worth,_Texas</span></a>

<b>Arlington </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">is a principal city in the U.S. state of Texas, located in Tarrant County. It is part of the Mid-Cities region of the Dallas–Fort Worth–Arlington metropolitan area.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Arlington is the fiftieth-most populous city in the United States, the seventh-most populous city in the state of Texas, and the largest city in the state that is not a county seat.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">The percentage of foreign-born persons in Arlington, Texas was  20.1% according to a 2009 Census.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Source: </span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arlington,_Texas" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arlington,_Texas</span></a>[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][vc_column width="1/3"][vc_column_text][awesome-weather location='Dallas Fort Worth Arlington TX' custom_bg_color='#78569F'][/vc_column_text][vc_widget_sidebar title="Other Industries" sidebar_id="shop"][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row el_class="parallax-section forms-rows" css=".vc_custom_1479126621357{margin-top: 50px !important;background-color: #373d67 !important;}"][vc_column][contact-form-7 id="1554"][/vc_column][/vc_row]]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>Houston, Sugar Land, Baytown, TX</title>
		<link>http://telelanguage.com/houston-sugar-land-baytown-tx/</link>
		<pubDate>Mon, 14 Nov 2016 12:34:53 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://telelanguage.com/?page_id=2840</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[[vc_row][vc_column width="2/3"][vc_column_text]<b>Telelanguage has been providing our customers with the </b><b>highest quality language services </b><b>since 1991 in Houston, Sugar Land, Baytown, TX. </b>We are a reliable and innovative leader in the language industry. We provide <a href="http://telelanguage.com/services/" target="_blank" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?hl=en&amp;q=http://telelanguage.com/services/&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1481138528295000&amp;usg=AFQjCNETQHH-PS-MUhGRsy0Y2DLUwaU1gw">interpretation and translation services</a> to over 1,400 organizations throughout the United States – <a href="http://telelanguage.com/industries/" target="_blank" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?hl=en&amp;q=http://telelanguage.com/industries/&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1481138528295000&amp;usg=AFQjCNEDWAaQPIufGCrnPCRM3TTenBHXAg">across all industries</a>.

<b>Immigrant Population</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">: 1,119,50 </span>

<b>Percent of Population</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">: 21.39% </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Houston traditionally has been home to a large number of Mexican and Latin American immigrants, but the city also has some of the largest Indian and Pakistani populations in the country. The city also has the biggest Nigerian community in the U.S.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Source: </span><a href="http://www.thedailybeast.com/galleries/2010/07/27/20-u-s-cities-with-the-most-immigrants.html" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">The Daily Beast</span></a>

<b>Houston</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> is the most populous city in Texas and the fourth-most populous city in the United States, located in Southeast Texas near the Gulf of Mexico.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Houston is multicultural, in part because of its many academic institutions and strong industries, as well as being a major port city. Over 90 languages are spoken in the city. It has among the youngest populations in the nation, partly due to an influx of immigrants into Texas. An estimated 400,000 illegal aliens reside in the Houston area.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">According to a 2009 Census, the percentage of foreign-born persons in Arlington, Virginia was 28.5%, ranking it 16th in the United States for foreign-born populations, and in addition, Hispanics made up 37.4% of Houston's population (2000 Census).</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Source: </span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Houston,_Texas" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Houston,_Texas</span></a>

<b>Sugar Land</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> is a city in the U.S. state of Texas. The city is within the Houston–The Woodlands–Sugar Land metropolitan area and Fort Bend County. It is one of the most affluent and fastest-growing cities in Texas, having grown more than 158 percent between 2000 and 2010.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Sugar Land has the highest concentration of Asians in Texas. Altogether, 35.3% of the city's population is Asian; 10.7% is Asian Indian, 11.5% is Chinese, 4.5% is Vietnamese and 2% is Filipino.</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">As of 2013, about one-third of the Asian population was Indian American, according to Harish Jajoo, a city council member of Indian origin. The Sugar Land area has Indian grocery stores, temples, several mosques and an Ismaili Center. Jajoo stated that the quality of the jobs, schools, and parks attracts people of Indian origin to Sugar Land.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Source: </span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sugar_Land,_Texas" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sugar_Land,_Texas</span></a>

<b>Baytown </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">is a city within Harris County and partially in Chambers County in the Gulf Coast region of the U.S. state of Texas. Located within the Houston–The Woodlands–Sugar Land metropolitan area, it lies along State Highway 146 and Interstate 10. It is the fourth-largest city within this metropolitan area. As of 2010, Baytown had a population of 71,802, and it had an estimated population of 76,127 in 2014. </span>[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][vc_column width="1/3"][vc_column_text][awesome-weather location='Houston Sugar Land Baytown TX' custom_bg_color='#78569F'][/vc_column_text][vc_widget_sidebar title="Other Industries" sidebar_id="shop"][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row el_class="parallax-section forms-rows" css=".vc_custom_1479126621357{margin-top: 50px !important;background-color: #373d67 !important;}"][vc_column][contact-form-7 id="1554"][/vc_column][/vc_row]]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>Las Vegas, Paradise, NV</title>
		<link>http://telelanguage.com/las-vegas-paradise-nv/</link>
		<pubDate>Mon, 14 Nov 2016 12:35:16 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://telelanguage.com/?page_id=2842</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[[vc_row][vc_column width="2/3"][vc_column_text]<b>Telelanguage has been providing our customers with the </b><b>highest quality language services </b><b>since 1991 in Las Vegas, Paradise, NV. </b>We are a reliable and innovative leader in the language industry. We provide <a href="http://telelanguage.com/services/" target="_blank" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?hl=en&amp;q=http://telelanguage.com/services/&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1481138528295000&amp;usg=AFQjCNETQHH-PS-MUhGRsy0Y2DLUwaU1gw">interpretation and translation services</a> to over 1,400 organizations throughout the United States – <a href="http://telelanguage.com/industries/" target="_blank" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?hl=en&amp;q=http://telelanguage.com/industries/&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1481138528295000&amp;usg=AFQjCNEDWAaQPIufGCrnPCRM3TTenBHXAg">across all industries</a>.

<b>Immigrant Population</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">: 1,073,591 </span>

<b>Immigrant Population</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">: 397,205 </span>

<b>Percent of Population</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">: 21.81% </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Las Vegas has become one of America’s fastest-growing cities in the 2000s, due in no small part to the large number of immigrants who have </span><a href="http://www.lasvegashomeman.com/docs/AmericasFastestGrowingCities.html" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">moved there</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">. With its large entertainment and tourism industry, the city easily attracts a large number of people seeking work, and it has one of the </span><a href="http://www.unlv.edu/centers/cdclv/healthnv/immigration.html" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">fastest-growing</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Asian and Hispanic populations in the country. </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Source: </span><a href="http://www.thedailybeast.com/galleries/2010/07/27/20-u-s-cities-with-the-most-immigrants.html" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">The Daily Beast</span></a>

<b>North Las Vegas </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">is a city in Clark County, Nevada, United States, located in the Las Vegas Valley. As of the 2010 census it had a population of 216,961, with an estimated population of 226,877 in 2013. </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">From a 2010 Census, Hispanic or Latino of any race were 38.8% of the population, and </span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Native_American_(U.S._Census)" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Native American</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">, 6.3%.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">According to a 2009 Census, the percentage of foreign-born persons in Las Vegas, Nevada was 24.9%, ranking it 26th in the United States for foreign-born populations.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Source: </span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/North_Las_Vegas,_Nevada" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/North_Las_Vegas,_Nevada</span></a>[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][vc_column width="1/3"][vc_column_text][awesome-weather location='Las Vegas Paradise NV' custom_bg_color='#78569F'][/vc_column_text][vc_widget_sidebar title="Other Industries" sidebar_id="shop"][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row el_class="parallax-section forms-rows" css=".vc_custom_1479126621357{margin-top: 50px !important;background-color: #373d67 !important;}"][vc_column][contact-form-7 id="1554"][/vc_column][/vc_row]]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>Riverside, San Bernardino, Ontario, CA</title>
		<link>http://telelanguage.com/riverside-san-bernardino-ontario-ca/</link>
		<pubDate>Mon, 14 Nov 2016 12:35:41 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://telelanguage.com/?page_id=2844</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[[vc_row][vc_column width="2/3"][vc_column_text]<b>Telelanguage has been providing our customers with the </b><b>highest quality language services </b><b>since 1991 in Riverside, San Bernardino, Ontario, CA. </b>We are a reliable and innovative leader in the language industry. We provide <a href="http://telelanguage.com/services/" target="_blank" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?hl=en&amp;q=http://telelanguage.com/services/&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1481138528295000&amp;usg=AFQjCNETQHH-PS-MUhGRsy0Y2DLUwaU1gw">interpretation and translation services</a> to over 1,400 organizations throughout the United States – <a href="http://telelanguage.com/industries/" target="_blank" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?hl=en&amp;q=http://telelanguage.com/industries/&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1481138528295000&amp;usg=AFQjCNEDWAaQPIufGCrnPCRM3TTenBHXAg">across all industries</a>.

<b>Immigrant Population</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">: 893,600 </span>

<b>Percent of Population</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">: 22.04% </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">The L.A. suburbs of Riverside, San Bernardino, and Ontario are home to one of the fastest-growing Asian-American populations in the country. While the area has mainly been known for its large number of immigrants from Mexico, the population of Mexican-born immigrants only makes up a little more than half of the region's foreign-born population.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Source: </span><a href="http://www.thedailybeast.com/galleries/2010/07/27/20-u-s-cities-with-the-most-immigrants.html" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">The Daily Beast</span></a>

<b>Riverside</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Riverside is a city in Riverside County, California, United States, located in the Inland Empire metropolitan area. Riverside is the county seat of the eponymous county and named for its location beside the Santa Ana River. It is the most populous city in the Inland Empire as well as Riverside County, and is located approximately 60 miles east of Los Angeles. It is also part of the Greater Los Angeles area. Riverside is the 59th most populous city in the United States and 12th most populous city in California.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">A 2010 Census reports the racial makeup of Riverside California to include 7.4% Asian (1.7% Filipino, 1.6% Chinese, 1.1% Korean, 1.0% Vietnamese, 0.8% Indian, 0.3% Japanese, 0.1% Pakistani), and Hispanic or Latino of any race were 148,953 persons (49.0%); 41.8% of Riverside's population is Mexican, 1.1% Guatemalan, 1.0% Salvadoran, 0.7% Puerto Rican, 0.3% Cuban, 0.2% Nicaraguan, and 0.2% Colombian.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">According to a 2009 Census, the percentage of foreign-born persons in Riverside, California was 23.4%, ranking it 29th in the United States for foreign-born populations.</span>

&nbsp;

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Source: </span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Riverside,_California" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Riverside,_California</span></a>

<b>San Bernardino </b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">San Bernardino is a city located in the Riverside-San Bernardino metropolitan area (Inland Empire). It serves as the county seat of San Bernardino County, California, United States. As one of the Inland Empire's anchor cities, San Bernardino spans 81 square miles on the floor of the San Bernardino Valley, and has a population of 209,924 as of the 2010 census. San Bernardino is the 17th-largest city in California, and the 100th-largest city in the United States. San Bernardino is home to numerous diplomatic missions for the Inland Empire, being one of four cities in California with numerous consulates (the other three being </span><a href="http://telelanguage.com/LosAngeles-Long-Beach-Santa-Ana-CA" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Los Angeles</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">, </span><a href="http://telelanguage.com/San-Diego-Carlsbad-San-Marcos-CA/" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">San Diego</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> and </span><a href="http://telelanguage.com/San-Francisco-Oakland-Fremont-CA/" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">San Francisco</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">). The governments of Guatemala and Mexico have established their consulates in the downtown area of the city.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">The racial makeup of San Bernardino according to a 2010 Census included populations of (4.0%) Asian, 839 and Hispanic or Latino of any race were 125,994 persons (60.0%).</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Source: </span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/San_Bernardino,_California" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/San_Bernardino,_California</span></a>

<b>Ontario</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Ontario is a city located in southwestern San Bernardino County, California, 35 miles east of downtown Los Angeles. Located in the western part of the Inland Empire region, it lies just east of the Los Angeles county line and is part of the Greater Los Angeles Area. As of the 2010 Census, the city had a population of 163,924, up from 158,007 at the 2000 census, making it the county's fourth most populous city after San Bernardino, Fontana, and Rancho Cucamonga.</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><b>
</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">The city is home to the Ontario International Airport, which is the 15th busiest airport in the United States by cargo carried.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">The racial makeup of Ontario, California, according to a 2010 Census, included populations of (5.2%) Asian, and Hispanic or Latino of any race were 113,085 persons (69.0%).</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Source: </span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ontario,_California" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ontario,_California</span></a>[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][vc_column width="1/3"][vc_column_text][awesome-weather location='Riverside San Bernardino Ontario CA' custom_bg_color='#78569F'][/vc_column_text][vc_widget_sidebar title="Other Industries" sidebar_id="shop"][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row el_class="parallax-section forms-rows" css=".vc_custom_1479126621357{margin-top: 50px !important;background-color: #373d67 !important;}"][vc_column][contact-form-7 id="1554"][/vc_column][/vc_row]]]></content:encoded>
		<excerpt:encoded><![CDATA[]]></excerpt:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>San Diego, Carlsbad, San Marcos, CA</title>
		<link>http://telelanguage.com/san-diego-carlsbad-san-marcos-ca/</link>
		<pubDate>Mon, 14 Nov 2016 12:36:08 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://telelanguage.com/?page_id=2846</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[[vc_row][vc_column width="2/3"][vc_column_text]<b>Telelanguage has been providing our customers with the </b><b>highest quality language services </b><b>since 1991 in San Diego, Carlsbad, San Marcos, CA. </b>We are a reliable and innovative leader in the language industry. We provide <a href="http://telelanguage.com/services/" target="_blank" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?hl=en&amp;q=http://telelanguage.com/services/&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1481139307704000&amp;usg=AFQjCNGiYsioYG-OUZSJuij9fRH8TkZ4Cg">interpretation and translation services</a> to over 1,400 organizations throughout the United States – <a href="http://telelanguage.com/industries/" target="_blank" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?hl=en&amp;q=http://telelanguage.com/industries/&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1481139307704000&amp;usg=AFQjCNHhd6sHlRgxCfzogSLMn7gnsKqxgw">across all industries</a>.

<b>Immigrant Population</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">: 671,608 </span>

<b>Percent of Population</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">: 22.64% </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">San Diego’s foreign-born population surged 40 percent in the 1990s, far outpacing the rest of its growth. Given the city’s close proximity to the U.S.-Mexico border, San Diego has long had a complicated relationship with immigration. In 2010, the New American Museum opened in the city, dedicated to showing the plight of immigrants.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Source: </span><a href="http://www.thedailybeast.com/galleries/2010/07/27/20-u-s-cities-with-the-most-immigrants.html" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">The Daily Beast</span></a>

<b>San Diego</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">San Diego (Spanish for "Saint Didacus") is a major city in California. It is in San Diego County, on the coast of the Pacific Ocean in Southern California, approximately 120 miles south of Los Angeles and immediately adjacent to the border with Mexico.</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">With an estimated population of 1,394,928 as of July 1, 2015, San Diego is the eighth-largest city in the United States and second-largest in California. It is part of the San Diego–Tijuana conurbation, the second-largest transborder agglomeration between the US and a bordering country after Detroit–Windsor, with a population of 4,922,723 people. San Diego is known as "the birthplace of California.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">The 201o Census reported the ethnic makeup of San Diego to include 28.8% Hispanic or Latino (of any race);  24.9% of the total population were Mexican American, and 0.6% were Puerto Rican.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">According to a 2009 Census, the percentage of foreign-born persons in San Diego was 24.9% ranking it 25th in the United States for foreign-born populations.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Source: </span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/San_Diego" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/San_Diego</span></a>

<b>Carlsbad</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Carlsbad is an affluent seaside resort city occupying a 7-mile stretch of Pacific coastline in northern San Diego County, California. The city is 87 miles south of Los Angeles and 35 miles north of downtown San Diego and is part of the San Diego-Carlsbad, CA Metropolitan Statistical Area. Referred to as "The Village by the Sea" by locals, the city of Carlsbad is a tourist destination.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">As of the 2010 United States Census Carlsbad had a population of 105,328. The racial makeup of Carlsbad included populations of: 7,460 (7.1%) Asian, and Hispanic or Latino of any race were 13,988 persons (13.3%).</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Source: </span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carlsbad,_California" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carlsbad,_California</span></a>

<b>San Marcos</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">San Marcos is a city in the North County region of San Diego County in the U.S. state of California. As of the 2010 census, the city's population was 83,781. It is the site of California State University San Marcos. The city is bordered by Escondido to the east, Encinitas to the southwest, Carlsbad to the west, and Vista to the northwest.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">San Marcos has a diversity of races and ethnic groups common in suburban communities: Irish, Italian, Portuguese, German, Polish, Russian, Armenian, Iranian, Indian, Vietnamese, Chinese, Japanese, Filipino, Mexican, Salvadorian, Argentine, Cuban, Puerto Rican, Hawaiian and Samoan.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">The racial makeup of San Marcos according to a 2010 Census included populations of: 7,518 (9.0%) Asian, 322 (0.4%) Pacific Islander, 15,853 (18.9%) from other races, and 4,295 (5.1%) from two or more races. Hispanic or Latino of any race were 30,697 persons (36.6%).</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Source: </span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/San_Marcos,_California" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/San_Marcos,_California</span></a>[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][vc_column width="1/3"][vc_column_text][awesome-weather location='San Diego Carlsbad San Marcos CA' custom_bg_color='#78569F'][/vc_column_text][vc_widget_sidebar title="Other Industries" sidebar_id="shop"][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row el_class="parallax-section forms-rows" css=".vc_custom_1479126621357{margin-top: 50px !important;background-color: #373d67 !important;}"][vc_column][contact-form-7 id="1554"][/vc_column][/vc_row]]]></content:encoded>

		<wp:postmeta>
			<wp:meta_key><![CDATA[_yoast_wpseo_focuskw]]></wp:meta_key>

	<item>
		<title>Sacramento, Arden Arcade, Roseville, CA</title>
		<link>http://telelanguage.com/sacramento-arden-arcade-roseville-ca/</link>
		<pubDate>Mon, 14 Nov 2016 12:36:31 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://telelanguage.com/?page_id=2848</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[[vc_row][vc_column width="2/3"][vc_column_text]<b>Telelanguage has been providing our customers with the </b><b>highest quality language services </b><b>since 1991 in Sacramento, Arden Arcade, Roseville, CA. </b>We are a reliable and innovative leader in the language industry. We provide <a href="http://telelanguage.com/services/" target="_blank" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?hl=en&amp;q=http://telelanguage.com/services/&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1481139307704000&amp;usg=AFQjCNGiYsioYG-OUZSJuij9fRH8TkZ4Cg">interpretation and translation services</a> to over 1,400 organizations throughout the United States – <a href="http://telelanguage.com/industries/" target="_blank" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?hl=en&amp;q=http://telelanguage.com/industries/&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1481139307704000&amp;usg=AFQjCNHhd6sHlRgxCfzogSLMn7gnsKqxgw">across all industries</a>.

<b>Immigrant Population</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">: 358,499 </span>

<b>Percent of Total</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">: 17.21% </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">As the capital of California, Sacramento has long been a center for immigrants. The city started with a large Chinese population influx a century ago, and since then, the city has had nearly 16 percent of its population be foreign-born. </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Source: </span><a href="http://www.thedailybeast.com/galleries/2010/07/27/20-u-s-cities-with-the-most-immigrants.html" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">The Daily Beast</span></a>

<b>Sacramento</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Sacramento is the capital city of the U.S. state of California and the seat of Sacramento County. It is at the confluence of the Sacramento River and the American River in the northern portion of California's expansive Central Valley. Its estimated 2014 population of 485,199 made it the sixth-largest city in California, and the 35th largest city in the United States. Sacramento is the cultural and economic core of the Sacramento metropolitan area, which includes seven counties with a 2010 population of 2,414,783. Its metropolitan area is the fourth largest in California after the Greater Los Angeles area, the San Francisco Bay Area, and the San Diego metropolitan area, and is the 27th largest in the United States. In 2002, the Civil Rights Project at Harvard University conducted for TIME magazine named Sacramento "America's Most Diverse City".</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">The 2010 United States Census reported that Sacramento had a population of 466,488.</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">The racial makeup of Sacramento included populations of :</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">85,503 (17.8%) Asian (4.2% Chinese, 3.3% Hmong, 2.8% Filipino, 1.6% Indian, 1.4% Vietnamese, 1.2% Laotian, 1.2% Japanese, 0.3% Pakistani, 0.3% Korean, 0.3% Thai, 0.2% Cambodian)</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">6,655 (1.4%) Pacific Islander (0.6% Fijian, 0.2% Tongan, 0.2% Samoan)</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">5,291 (1.1%) Native American</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">57,573 (12.3%) other races</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">33,125 (7.1%) from two or more races.</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Hispanic or Latino of any race were 125,276 persons (26.9%); 22.6% of Sacramento's population is of Mexican heritage, 0.7% Puerto Rican, 0.5% Salvadoran, 0.2% Guatemalan, and 0.2% Nicaraguan. Non-Hispanic Whites were 34.5% of the population in 2010,down from 71.4% in 1970.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">According to a 2009 Census, the percentage of foreign-born persons in San Diego was 21.9% ranking it 32nd in the United States for foreign-born populations.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Source</span><b>: </b><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sacramento,_California" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sacramento,_California
</span></a><b>
</b><b>Arden-Arcade</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Arden-Arcade is a census-designated place (CDP) in Sacramento County, California, United States. The population was 92,186 at the 2010 census. It is east of the city of Sacramento and west of the community of Carmichael.</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Arden-Arcade is a principal locality of the Sacramento–Arden-Arcade–Roseville Metropolitan Statistical Area.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">The 2010 United States Census reported that Arden-Arcade had a population of 92,186. The population density was 5,144.5 people per square mile. The racial makeup of Arden-Arcade included populations of: (5.6%) Asian (1.3% Indonesian, 1.0% Chinese, 0.6% Taiwanese, 0.5% Japanese, 0.5% Korean, 0.4% Hmong, 1.3% Other), and Hispanic or Latino of any race were 17,147 persons (18.6%).</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Source: </span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arden-Arcade,_California" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arden-Arcade,_California</span></a>

<b>Roseville</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Roseville (formerly, Roseville Junction, Junction, and Grider's) is the largest city in Placer County, California, located in the Sacramento metropolitan area. As of January 1, 2015, the state Department of Finance estimated the city's population to be 128,382.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">In 1985 the population stood at 28,988 people. Five years later it was 44,685 people, and by the year 2000 it was 74,234 people. Some of this growth was fueled by the location of major employers, such as Hewlett Packard (in 1979) and NEC (in 1983). The population as of 2014 was 126,956 people.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">The 2010 United States Census reported that Roseville had a population of 118,788. The population density was 3,279.4 people per square mile. The racial makeup of Roseville included populations of: (8.4%) Asian (3.1% Filipino, 2.0% Indian, 1.0% Chinese, 0.6% Japanese, 0.6% Vietnamese, 0.5% Korean, 0.8% Other), and Hispanic or Latino of any race were 17,359 persons (14.6%).</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Source: </span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roseville,_California" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roseville,_California</span></a>[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][vc_column width="1/3"][vc_column_text][awesome-weather location='Sacramento Arden Arcade Roseville CA' custom_bg_color='#78569F'][/vc_column_text][vc_widget_sidebar title="Other Industries" sidebar_id="shop"][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row el_class="parallax-section forms-rows" css=".vc_custom_1479126621357{margin-top: 50px !important;background-color: #373d67 !important;}"][vc_column][contact-form-7 id="1554"][/vc_column][/vc_row]]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>Phoenix, Mesa, Scottsdale, AZ</title>
		<link>http://telelanguage.com/phoenix-mesa-scottsdale-az/</link>
		<pubDate>Mon, 14 Nov 2016 12:36:49 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://telelanguage.com/?page_id=2850</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[[vc_row][vc_column width="2/3"][vc_column_text]<b>Telelanguage has been providing our customers with the </b><b>highest quality language services </b><b>since 1991 in Phoenix, Mesa, Scottsdale, AZ. </b>We are a reliable and innovative leader in the language industry. We provide <a href="http://telelanguage.com/services/" target="_blank" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?hl=en&amp;q=http://telelanguage.com/services/&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1481139307704000&amp;usg=AFQjCNGiYsioYG-OUZSJuij9fRH8TkZ4Cg">interpretation and translation services</a> to over 1,400 organizations throughout the United States – <a href="http://telelanguage.com/industries/" target="_blank" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?hl=en&amp;q=http://telelanguage.com/industries/&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1481139307704000&amp;usg=AFQjCNHhd6sHlRgxCfzogSLMn7gnsKqxgw">across all industries</a>.

<b>Immigrant Population</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">: 692,038 </span>

<b>Percent of Total</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">: 16.63% </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Source: </span><a href="http://www.thedailybeast.com/galleries/2010/07/27/20-u-s-cities-with-the-most-immigrants.html" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">The Daily Beast</span></a>

<b>Phoenix</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Phoenix is the capital and most populous city of the U.S. state of Arizona. With 1,563,025 people (as of 2015), Phoenix is the sixth most populous city nationwide, the most populous state capital in the United States, and the only state capital with a population of more than 1 million residents.</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Phoenix is the anchor of the Phoenix metropolitan area, also known as the Valley of the Sun, which in turn is a part of the Salt River Valley. The metropolitan area is the 12th largest by population in the United States, with approximately 4.3 million people as of 2010.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">According to the 2010 Census, of the 1,342,803 residents over 5 years of age, 63.5% spoke only English, 30.6% spoke Spanish at home, 2.5% spoke another Indo-European language, 2.1% spoke Asian or Islander languages, with the remaining 1.4% speaking other languages. About 15.7% of non-English speakers reported speaking English less than "very well". The largest national ancestries reported were Mexican (35.9%), German (15.3%), Irish (10.3%), English (9.4%), Black (6.5%), Italian (4.5%), French (2.7%), Polish (2.5%), American Indian (2.2%), and Scottish (2.0%).[126] Hispanics or Latinos of any race make up 40.8% of the population. Of these the largest groups are at 35.9% Mexican, 0.6% Puerto Rican, 0.5% Guatemalan, 0.3% Salvadoran, 0.3% Cuban.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">According to a 2009 Census, the percentage of foreign-born persons in Phoenix was 21.7% ranking it 34th in the United States for foreign-born populations.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Source: </span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phoenix,_Arizona" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phoenix,_Arizona</span></a>

<b>Mesa </b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Mesa is a city in Maricopa County, in the U.S. state of Arizona, and is a suburb located about 20 miles east of Phoenix. Mesa is the central city of the East Valley section of the Phoenix Metropolitan Area. It is bordered by Tempe on the west, the Salt River Pima-Maricopa Indian Community on the north, Chandler and Gilbert on the south, and Apache Junction on the east. As of the 2010 Census Mesa became Arizona's center of population.</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Mesa is the third-largest city in Arizona, after Phoenix and Tucson, and the 38th-largest city in the US. The city is home to 439,041 people as of 2010 according to the Census Bureau. Mesa is home to numerous higher education facilities including the Polytechnic campus of Arizona State University.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">As of the Census of 2010 the racial make-up of Mesa included populations of: 2.2% Native American, 2.00% Asian, and 24.0% of the population were Hispanic or Latino of any race.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">According to a 2009 Census, the percentage of foreign-born persons in Mesa, Arizona was 12.2% ranking it 59th in the United States for foreign-born populations.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Source: </span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mesa,_Arizona" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mesa,_Arizona</span></a>

<b>Scottsdale</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Scottsdale is a city in the eastern part of Maricopa County, Arizona, adjacent to the Greater Phoenix Area. Named Scottsdale in 1894 after founder Winfield Scott and incorporated in 1951 with a population of 2000, the 2015 population of the city is estimated to be 236,839 according to the U.S. Census Bureau. The New York Times described downtown Scottsdale as "a desert version of Miami's South Beach" and as having "plenty of late night partying and a buzzing hotel scene." Its slogan is "The West's Most Western Town."</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">As of the census of 2010, there were 217,385 people. The population density was 1,181.4 inhabitants per square mile. The racial makeup of Scottsdale included populations of 3.33% Asian, and 8.84% of the population were Hispanic or Latino of any race.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">According to a 2009 Census, the percentage of foreign-born persons in Scottsdale, Arizona was 12.6% ranking it 56th in the United States for foreign-born populations.</span>[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][vc_column width="1/3"][vc_widget_sidebar title="Other Industries" sidebar_id="shop"][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row el_class="parallax-section forms-rows" css=".vc_custom_1479126621357{margin-top: 50px !important;background-color: #373d67 !important;}"][vc_column][contact-form-7 id="1554"][/vc_column][/vc_row]]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>Boston, Cambridge, Quincy, MA</title>
		<link>http://telelanguage.com/boston-cambridge-quincy-ma/</link>
		<pubDate>Mon, 14 Nov 2016 12:37:14 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://telelanguage.com/?page_id=2852</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[[vc_row][vc_column width="2/3"][vc_column_text]<b>Telelanguage has been providing our customers with the </b><b>highest quality language services </b><b>since 1991 in Boston, Cambridge, Quincy, MA. </b>We are a reliable and innovative leader in the language industry. We provide <a href="http://telelanguage.com/services/" target="_blank" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?hl=en&amp;q=http://telelanguage.com/services/&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1481139307704000&amp;usg=AFQjCNGiYsioYG-OUZSJuij9fRH8TkZ4Cg">interpretation and translation services</a> to over 1,400 organizations throughout the United States – <a href="http://telelanguage.com/industries/" target="_blank" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?hl=en&amp;q=http://telelanguage.com/industries/&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1481139307704000&amp;usg=AFQjCNHhd6sHlRgxCfzogSLMn7gnsKqxgw">across all industries</a>.

<b>Immigrant Population</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">: 716,264 </span>

<b>Percent of Total</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">: 15.94% </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Boston long had a history as a haven for Irish immigrants, but the city's immigrant population continued to grow, even while similar cities were experiencing declines. The reasons for Boston's immigration increase are not clear, but many foreign-born residents probably came to attend the city's numerous universities or to work in the high-tech industry. </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Source: </span><a href="http://www.thedailybeast.com/galleries/2010/07/27/20-u-s-cities-with-the-most-immigrants.html" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">The Daily Beast</span></a>

<b>Boston</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">According to a 2009 Census, the percentage of foreign-born persons in Boston was 25.1% ranking it 24th in the United States for foreign-born populations.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Boston is the capital and most populous city of the Commonwealth of Massachusetts in the United States. The city proper covers 48 square miles (124 km2) with an estimated population of 667,137 in 2015, making it the largest city in New England and the 23rd most populous city in the United States. Boston is the economic and cultural anchor of a substantially larger metropolitan area called Greater Boston, home to 4.7 million people and the tenth-largest metropolitan statistical area in the country.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">People of Irish descent form the largest single ethnic group in the city, making up 15.8% of the population, followed by Italians, accounting for 8.3% of the population. People of West Indian and Caribbean ancestry are another sizable group, at 6.0%, about half of whom are of Haitian ancestry. Over 27,000 Chinese Americans made their home in Boston city proper in 2013, and the city hosts a growing Chinatown accommodating heavily traveled Chinese-owned bus lines to and from Chinatown, Manhattan in New York City. Some neighborhoods, such as Dorchester, have received an influx of people of Vietnamese ancestry in recent decades. Neighborhoods such as Jamaica Plain and Roslindale have experienced a growing number of Dominican Americans.[129] The city and greater area also has a growing immigrant population of South Asians, including the tenth-largest Indian community in the country.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">The city, especially the East Boston neighborhood, has a significant Hispanic community. In 2010, Hispanics in Boston were mostly of Puerto Rican (30,506 or 4.9% of total city population), Dominican (25,648 or 4.2% of total city population), Salvadoran (10,850 or 1.8% of city population), Colombian (6,649 or 1.1% of total city population), Mexican (5,961 or 1.0% of total city population), and Guatemalan (4,451 or 0.7% of total city population) ethnic origin. Hispanics of all national origins totaled 107,917 in 2010. In Greater Boston, these numbers grew significantly, with Puerto Ricans numbering 175,000+, Dominicans 95,000+, Salvadorans 40,000+, Guatemalans 31,000+, Mexicans 25,000+, and Colombians numbering 22,000+.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Source: </span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boston" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boston</span></a>

<b>Cambridge</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Cambridge is a city in Middlesex County, Massachusetts, United States, in the Boston metropolitan area. Situated directly north of the city of Boston, across the Charles River, it was named in honor of the University of Cambridge in the United Kingdom, an important center of the Puritan theology embraced by the town's founders. Cambridge is home to two of the world's most highly regarded universities, Harvard University and the Massachusetts Institute of Technology. Cambridge has also been home to Radcliffe College, once one of the leading colleges for women in the United States before it merged with Harvard. According to the 2010 Census, the city's population was 105,162. As of July 2014, it was the fifth most populous city in the state, behind Boston, Worcester, Springfield and Lowell.</span>

<b>Quincy</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Quincy is a city in Norfolk County, Massachusetts, United States. It is a major part of Metropolitan Boston and is Boston's immediate southern suburb. Its population in 2010 was 92,271, making it the 8th largest city in the state. Known as the "City of Presidents," Quincy is the birthplace of two U.S. presidents — John Adams and his son John Quincy Adams — as well as John Hancock, a President of the Continental Congress and the first signer of the Declaration of Independence.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">For more than a century, Quincy was home to a thriving granite industry; the city was also the site of the Granite Railway, the United States' first commercial railroad. Shipbuilding at the Fore River Shipyard was another key part of the city's economy. In the 20th century, both Howard Johnson's and Dunkin' Donuts were founded in the city.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">According to the 2010 Census the racial makeup of the city included populations of: 24.0% Asian (15.6% Chinese, 3.2% Vietnamese, 2.6% Indian[40]), and Hispanic or Latino of any race were 4.6% of the population. </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">33.5% were of Irish (making Quincy the most Irish American city in the entire United States), 12.7% Italian and 5.0% English ancestry according to Census 2000. </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Languages: 77.1% spoke only English, while 8.0% spoke Chinese or Mandarin, 2.6% Cantonese, 1.9% Spanish, 1.5% Vietnamese and 1.3% Italian in their homes.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Source: </span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quincy,_Massachusetts" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400;">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quincy,_Massachusetts</span></a>[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][vc_column width="1/3"][vc_column_text][awesome-weather location='Boston Cambridge Quincy MA' custom_bg_color='#78569F'][/vc_column_text][vc_widget_sidebar title="Other Industries" sidebar_id="shop"][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row el_class="parallax-section forms-rows" css=".vc_custom_1479126621357{margin-top: 50px !important;background-color: #373d67 !important;}"][vc_column][contact-form-7 id="1554"][/vc_column][/vc_row]]]></content:encoded>

		<wp:postmeta>
			<wp:meta_key><![CDATA[_yoast_wpseo_focuskw]]></wp:meta_key>
