	<item>
		<title>Interpreter Don’ts: How to Avoid Interference for More Quality Interpretations Part II</title>
		<link>http://telelanguage.com/interpreter-donts-avoid-interference-quality-interpretations-part-ii/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 23 Aug 2016 16:41:37 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://telelanguage.com/?p=2432</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-2565" src="http://telelanguage.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/08/Blog_Part-2-Interpreter-Don.jpg" alt="Alt=&quot;Interpreter Donts&quot;" width="1140" height="505" />In the first part of our <a href="http://blog.telelanguage.com/?p=246">“don’ts” blog</a>, we covered the basic ways you can avoid obstruction during a meeting or appointment with a certified interpreter. As a follow-up, here are a few more ways to make sure appointments with <a href="http://www.telelanguage.com">face to face or telephonic interpreters</a> runs smoothly:

<strong> </strong><strong>The Interpreter is not a babysitter/escort:</strong>  A prompt and professional interpreter will generally arrive a few minutes early.  While waiting for the appointment to start, it’s not appropriate to expect your interpreter to direct or escort a client or patient to a room or meeting. Additionally, an interpreter should never be used to keep a client or patient company before appointments.

<strong> </strong><strong>Try speaking in a different language:</strong>  Even if you think you know some basic phrases, mispronunciations of a language you’re not familiar with may result in delays. The interpreter will use their training and skills to professionally relay the interaction back to the client or patient, but you never want to create a situation where the interpreter themselves might not understand you.

<strong> </strong><strong>Speak over the interpreter:</strong>   Speaking over the interpreter while they’re in the process of interpreting will create unnecessary setbacks, and you may have to start the sentence over and repeat yourself.  When an interpreter is speaking to the patient or client, there shouldn’t be any others in the room engaged in conversations.  An interpreter’s job is to provide total understanding for the person that doesn’t speak the language, which means they have the right to know what’s being said in the room if others are present. This puts the interpreter in a demanding situation, not to mention the extra noise in the room is distracting.

<strong> </strong><strong>Expect the interpreter to explain what you mean:</strong> An interpreter will not explain to the client what you meant to say, they will interpret what you’ve said word for word. Just like you wouldn’t ask for their opinion, you wouldn’t expect an interpreter to try to explain details of the subject matter. You also shouldn’t use the interpreter to deliver results to a patient, or take charge of a meeting.

Interpreters are a vital resource, and their ability to promote understanding and communication in any situation is important.  When you provide proper settings combined with good conduct, you’ll receive quality interpretations and the ability to fulfill your time to its maximum potential. If you’re looking for professional certified interpreters, <a href="http://www.telelanguage.com/">Telelanguage</a> offers around the clock service, every day of the year, including holidays. Connect to an interpreter in just seconds, and let Telelanguage show you why we are the leading language service provider in the industry!

&nbsp;
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Quality interpretations by our interpreters in over 200 languages!</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Call us today at </strong><a href="http://blog.telelanguage.com/interpreter-donts-how-to-avoid-interference-for-more-quality-interpretations-part-ii/888-983-5352"><strong>888-983-5352</strong></a><strong> </strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Providing expert interpretations telephonically or face to face!</em></p>]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title></title>
		<link>http://telelanguage.com/?p=3227</link>
		<pubDate>Mon, 30 Nov -0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://telelanguage.com/?p=3227</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<span style="font-weight: 400;">Whether you have an international business or you’re ready to expand your services, we live in a global market. Today, telephone interpreters are an important part of growing an international company, improving business-to-business communications, and maximizing the success of global outreach.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Bringing a professional telephone interpreter on conference calls for your non-English-speaking and limited-English-speaking clients ensures that you get your message across effectively, efficiently, and shows your customers that you care. </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">According to the </span><a href="https://www.bls.gov/ooh/media-and-communication/interpreters-and-translators.htm"><span style="font-weight: 400;">U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">, over 61,000 people work as translators and interpreters. But not all interpreters are right for your business. So how do you select the right telephone interpreter for your conference call?</span>

<i><span style="font-weight: 400;">Here are five things to consider when looking for a telephone interpreter for conference calls:</span></i>

&nbsp;

<b>Professional Telephone Interpreters</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">When it comes to expanding your business into global markets, you want to guarantee that no part of your message is left to chance. Business interpretation and translation can be highly specialized for many fields. Using an industry-certified interpreter with knowledge of your business market and specific terminology is critical to effective communication in the target language. A language service provider should offer a filter-based qualification interpreter connect feature to provide the most qualified interpreter for your situation.</span>

&nbsp;

<b>Telephone Interpreter Protocol</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">While your non-English-speaking clients may expect or be informed that interpreter will be present, you should always introduce the interpreter at the start of your conference call to avoid any confusion. Introducing your interpreter upfront will allow your clients to adjust their speaking naturally to allow for the most quality interpreting. A professional interpreter will also be aware of the etiquette of the client country and culture for sound interpretations.</span>

&nbsp;

<b>Flexibility</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Although many international business meetings may be planned in advance, you should consider a reliable language service provider who can also provide </span><a href="http://telelanguage.com/tips-working-business-interpreter/"><span style="font-weight: 400;">business interpreters on the spot</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> for unexpected situations that may arise. For these situations, fast connect times is also important to keep the flow of communication and professionalism.</span>

&nbsp;

<b>Complete Language Solution</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Using telephone interpreters for business conference calls is an efficient and cost-effective way to get your company’s message across, but not all meetings will be confined to a conference call. Choosing a language services provider with a full range of interpretation and translation options, such as Video Remote Interpreting (</span><a href="http://telelanguage.com/video-remote-interpreting-infographic/"><span style="font-weight: 400;">VRI</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">), On-site Interpreting, and Document Translation gives businesses the ability to plan for every type of situation, make productive use of cutting-edge technology, and consistently meet client needs.</span>

&nbsp;

<b>24/7 Accessibility</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Language barriers won’t always arise when it’s convenient. Your business may operate 9-5, but your international clients don’t. While freelance and in-house interpreters cannot be available 24/7, a dedicated language service provider should be able to provide you with the language solutions you need at any time - 24 hours a days, 7 days a week, 365 days a year.</span>

&nbsp;

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Your company’s message and communication is not something to leave to chance in a global market. You need more than just an interpreter who speaks the language of your client. When seeking a telephone interpreter for business, you want to use these tips to select an interpreter or </span><a href="http://telelanguage.com/how-to-choose-language-service-provider/"><span style="font-weight: 400;">dedicated language services</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> provider that reflects your brand’s professionalism, can offer a complete language services solution and allows your company to grow and scale as you need it.</span>

&nbsp;

<i><span style="font-weight: 400;">Telelanguage has been a leading provider of telephonic interpretation services since 1991. We offer a complete package of language services to fit our clients’ needs: On-site Interpretation, Over-the-Phone Interpretation, Video Remote Interpretation and Document Translation. Whether you need a last-minute telephone interpreter for your conference call, an on-site appointment, or document translation, our network of 2000+ professional interpreters and translators are ready to provide understanding in 250 languages...24/7/365.  </span></i>

<i><span style="font-weight: 400;">Looking for a reliable language service provider or thinking about switching? Telelanguage can help. Contact us if you have any questions, or request a </span></i><a href="http://telelanguage.com/contact-us/"><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">free demo</span></i></a><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">. </span></i>
<p style="text-align: center;"><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">Superior Language Support in 250 Languages.</span></i></p>

		<title>Getting Ahead: Interpretation Services Technology</title>
		<link>http://telelanguage.com/?p=3243</link>
		<pubDate>Mon, 30 Nov -0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://telelanguage.com/?p=3243</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<span style="font-weight: 400;">"Technology made large populations possible; large populations now make technology indispensable." – Joseph Wood Krutch</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Ask people how they feel about technology and you may get varied answers. While the topic of technological advancement can be a charged issue for individuals, Telelanguage believes that for the world of interpretation services, technology is a way to bring people of all cultural and language backgrounds together for greater communication, understanding and efficiency.  Advances in Interpretation Services Technology coupled with excellent customer services is a win for all industries, from medical to business, in need of language access.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Telelanguage has been an innovative leader in the language services industry for more than 25 years, providing clients with superior-trained and certified interpreters to eliminate language barriers and help you serve your LEP, deaf and hard of hearing, and non-English-speaking clients and communities. Our first priorities have always been to provide our customers with the highest-quality language services and dedicated customer service—technology only helps us to continue and improve on those priorities and build maximum value for a complete language services solution.</span>

&nbsp;

<H2>Interpretation Services Technology Leading the Way</H2>

&nbsp;

<H3>Video Remote Interpreting (VRI)</H3>
<a href="http://telelanguage.com/services/video-remote-interpretation/"><img src="http://telelanguage.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/Video-Remote-Interpreting-300x176.jpg" alt="video-remote-interpreting" width="300" height="176" class="alignright size-medium wp-image-2724" /></a>
<i><span style="font-weight: 400;">What is it?</span></i>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">VRI technology is a video telecommunication service that uses web cameras or videophones to provide sign language or spoken language interpreting services via a remote interpreter. </span>

<i><span style="font-weight: 400;">How does it help?</span></i>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">VRI has changed the way services can be provided. Bridging the gap between telephonic interpretation and on-site interpretation, VRI has become an integral part of any language service plan. Video Remote Interpreting allows for the highest quality interpretations, second only to On-site interpretation, and is a perfect solution for on-demand situations where visual contact with the interpreter is necessary or helpful in your communication.</span>

<i><span style="font-weight: 400;">The Telelanguage difference</span></i>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Telelanguage offers state-of-the-art VRI technology. We use a robust and highly secure business class video connectivity platform that is accessible from any customer office or site. We make video easier than ever using standard laptop or desktop equipment available at the customer’s site.  We provide </span><a href="http://telelanguage.com/services/video-remote-interpretation/"><span style="font-weight: 400;">VRI software</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> and user interfaces at zero cost to our customers.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">VRI services can also be a cost-effective solution as Telelanguage does not charge hourly minimums or extra expenses.</span>

&nbsp;

<H3>Scheduling Software for Language Service Providers</H3>

<i><span style="font-weight: 400;">What is it?</span></i>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Usually a web-based tool, scheduling software is a solution designed to simplify and streamline management of interpreters and interpreting services for LSPs.</span>

<i><span style="font-weight: 400;">How does it help?</span></i>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">In 2015, there were <a href="https://www.statista.com/topics/2152/language-services-industry-in-the-us/" target="_blank">almost 50 thousand people working</a> in interpreting and translation services in the United States. Needless to say, interpreter management can be a time-consuming task, and an inability to keep up with interpreter requests is simply not an option. For language service providers, interpretation management software is a necessary technology. The key is customization capabilities, ease of use, and </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">flexibility of use/scale.</span>

<i><span style="font-weight: 400;">The Telelanguage difference</span></i>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Telelanguage makes it easy for language service providers to manage face-to-face interpretation requests with the Global Interpreter Platform (GIP), a web-based tool and </span><a href="http://telelanguage.com/scheduling-software-for-language-service-providers/"><span style="font-weight: 400;">all-inclusive interpretation scheduling</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> solution. </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Multi-functional, we make invoicing clients, scheduling and paying interpreters, and reporting easy from anywhere in the world. Telelanguage offers flexible GIP usage, designed for interpreter service providers of all sizes and built for multiple industries. We also provide our customers with 24/7 technical support through our dedicated team of IT professionals.</span>

&nbsp;

<H3>Telephonic Interpretation Technology</H3>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Telelanguage is a leading telephonic interpretation provider. Our effective, reliable, solutions, dedicated customer support, and performance improvement services have allowed us to provide our clients with the highest language services since 1991. Leading the way in cutting-edge technology, advanced features and real-time data access is the difference it takes in the fast-paced world of language services.</span>

<i><span style="font-weight: 400;">Advanced Features in Telephone Interpreting</span></i>

&nbsp;
<ul>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Automated Interpreter Connect</span></li>
</ul>
<ul>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Filter-based Qualification Interpreter Connect</span></li>
</ul>
<ul>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Online Tracking System / Account Management</span></li>
</ul>
<ul>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Performance Improvement Reviews </span></li>
</ul>
<ul>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Customized Data Reports</span></li>
</ul>
&nbsp;

<span style="font-weight: 400;">The world of interpretation services technology moves rapidly. We understand that our customers need to solve communication barriers quickly and Telelanguage offers our clients the </span><a href="http://telelanguage.com/services/telephonic-interpretation/"><span style="font-weight: 400;">fastest telephonic connection times</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> in the industry. </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Technology that allows for more efficient processes and expands the ability to provide services on demand is crucial all businesses. The language services industry is </span><a href="http://telelanguage.com/infographic-language-services-industry/"><span style="font-weight: 400;">changing rapidly</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">, and less innovative (more traditional) providers of interpreter services may not be able to keep up with the growing needs of businesses to make the best use of new interpretation services technology.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Telelanguage offers robust technology to support our clients. Our individually customized rate plans and always competitive rates, combined with smart technology and dedicated customer support makes the difference for our clients and the communities they serve. </span>

&nbsp;

<i><span style="font-weight: 400;">Complete language services solutions to fit your needs: On-site Interpretation, Over-the-Phone Interpretation, Video Remote Interpretation and Document Translation. Whether you need a last-minute telephone interpreter, an on-site appointment, or more efficient technology to drive business growth, Telelanguage can help! Our network of 2000+ professional interpreters and translators are ready to provide understanding in 250 languages…24/7/365.  </span></i>

<i><span style="font-weight: 400;">Looking for a more reliable language service provider or thinking about switching? Contact us for a </span></i><i><span style="font-weight: 400;"><a href="http://telelanguage.com/contact-us/">free demo</a> or chat with our team of specialists live.</span></i>

	<item>
		<title>Interpreter Don’ts: How to Avoid Interference for More Quality Interpretations</title>
		<link>http://telelanguage.com/interpreter-donts-avoid-interference-quality-interpretations/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 23 Aug 2016 16:42:25 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://telelanguage.com/?p=2434</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[A session or appointment with a face to face or telephonic interpreter needs to run as smoothly as possible to maximize efficiency.  You might not realize it, but an interpreter’s job is extremely demanding, and the way we interact with them has the potential to cause or add stress, or even prolong the session. What can we do to avoid interference and deliberate disruptions, ensuring quality interpretations so that everyone mutually benefits from time with a<a href="http://www.telelanguage.com/"> professional certified interpreter</a>?

<strong>Question the Interpreter:</strong> When hiring a professional certified interpreter,  you can rest assured they’ve received necessary language and technical skill education, as well as passed and obtained current certifications for your state. If you stop the session to inquire what they interpreted to the other party, the interpreter will have to answer you, then interpret to the others in the meeting or appointment what you asked. Stopping the session will only cause unnecessary delays, not to mention frustration to all involved.

<strong> </strong><strong>Argue/use the interpreter to defend you:</strong> Sometimes we need an interpreter in a mediation type situation, where high tensions and emotions may flare up. While hiding emotions in some cases may be hard, it’s important to remember your interpreter is there to be a neutral presence, and shouldn’t be brought into the middle of the discussion.  Turning to the interpreter for advice, or trying to get them to side with you will only hold up the appointment when the interpreter or other people in the party have to stop and redirect the conversation.

<strong> </strong><strong>Ask the interpreter go beyond the original assignment</strong>: There are instances when an interpreter and the client may have agreed on a locked amount of time. In some cases, the job for an interpreter is not over until satisfaction with a meeting or appointment has been met. Because of this, it’s important to be conscious of time and to not spring extra work or try to squeeze in anything other than what was agreed on before the appointment or meeting.

<strong> </strong><strong>Lack of prep tools for the interpreter:</strong>  In some situations, like  an emergency, there is no way to fully prepare your interpreter before they begin. If you have an appointment and are able, sending the interpreter prep information before they arrive can prevent spending time before the meeting or appointment to go over the material and ensure the most quality interpretations.

Taking steps to ensure that the interpreter’s role is acknowledged will make for a positive session with the highest quality interpretations. If you’re looking for a professional certified interpreter for your next meeting or appointment, allow <a href="http://www.telelanguage.com/telephonic-interpretation/industrieswesupport">Telelanguage </a>to assist you. With over 20 years in the language service industry, we are backed up by a team of 2,000 certified interpreters knowledgeable in 200 languages.  We provide professionalism and expertise, as well as speedy connections and reliable service 24 hours a day, 7 days a week, 365 days a year. Now, for even faster connections to a live interpreter wherever you’re at worldwide, download our free app for iPhone <a href="https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/telelanguage-services/id630044808?mt=8">here</a>!

<strong> </strong>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Qualified, expert, and certified interpreters!</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Call us today at </strong><a href="http://blog.telelanguage.com/interpreter-donts-how-to-avoid-interference-for-more-quality-interpretations/888-983-5352"><strong>888-983-5352</strong></a><strong> </strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Providing quality and expert interpretations telephonically or face to face</em></p>
<em>!</em>]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>Why Choose a Certified Interpreter vs. a Non Certified Interpreter?</title>
		<link>http://telelanguage.com/choose-certified-vs-non-certified-interpreter/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 23 Aug 2016 16:43:14 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://telelanguage.com/?p=2435</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[When language barriers arise in pressing situations, you might think the easier option would to call on a friend or a family member to offer lingual assistance. While it may seem convenient, there are important reasons for <a href="http://www.telelanguage.com">choosing professional certified interpreters</a> to facilitate the meeting, appointment or conference. We’ve listed the four most important reasons to choose a certified interpreter below:

<strong>Professionalism</strong> – Regardless if you require a face to face or telephonic interpreter, the meeting, appointment, or session will be a consistent and flawless experience in professionalism. Over the course of <a href="http://blog.telelanguage.com/">our past blogs</a>, we’ve built on the fact that certified interpreters are consciously aware that they’re held to the highest standards, which includes how they conduct themselves to you.

<strong>Confidentiality</strong> – Interpreters that have received certifications are held to a strict code of conduct, which includes confidentiality. With a certified interpreter, you will never walk away from a session feeling like critical information could be breached. Alternatively, a doctor may not wish to disclose parts of a diagnosis to a family member or a friend that has come along to help due to privacy issues. A certified interpreter offers security that your information will not leave the room.

<strong>Knowledge of complex vocabulary</strong> – A major advantage a certified interpreter has over a friend or family member is the ability to interpret complex vocabulary. A certified interpreter will also have engaged in rigorous testing of their skills and knowledge in the language of their specialized field. A medical or court interpreter will be tasked with memorizing and understanding the definitions of terms in addition to their understanding of the language.  A family member or friend might unintentionally alter information in the process of trying to interpret back to you. Understanding of the content could potentially be lost, or you may receive a highly inaccurate interpretation.

<strong>Trustworthy interpretations</strong> – A certified interpreter has been trained to handle complex sentences, or interpret different conversations that could be happening simultaneously. The certified interpreter will also remain neutral during the meeting or appointment, and never offer personal opinions. They also understand that you are at liberty to be able to know the full context of the information that’s being interpreted to you, in its true form without anything being left out. A family member might hold back if they feel it might be something offensive, or not feel comfortable relaying portions of information.

When hiring professional certified interpreters, all of the above requirements will be applied to your session. If you’re looking for a <a href="http://www.telelanguage.com/onsite-interpretation">reputable company with qualified and skilled interpreters </a>that have met all certification specifications, you can depend on Telelanguage. Having been in business for over 20 years, Telelanguage’s 2,000 interpreters are ready to speak in 200 languages.  Expect fast connections, face-to-face arrivals within 30 minutes of when the appointment was made, and the expertise that can only come from a certified interpreter. Now for even faster connections, download our <a href="https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/telelanguage-services/id630044808?mt=8">free app for iPhone</a> and reach a live interpreter in just seconds!

&nbsp;
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Professional, expert, and certified interpreters!</strong></p>

<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Providing quality and expert interpretations telephonically or face to face!</em></p>]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>Face to Face Interpreters: How to Make a Good First Impression</title>
		<link>http://telelanguage.com/face-face-interpreters-make-good-first-impression/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 23 Aug 2016 16:43:58 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://telelanguage.com/?p=2438</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[As a face to face interpreter, you’re called to interact with the general public on a daily basis. The first impression you make could be the difference of whether you’re remembered or re-hired. Regardless of being freelance, or working for an <a href="http://www.telelanguage.com/">interpreter service provider</a>, the first impression is a representation of yourself. You’ve most likely already <a href="http://blog.telelanguage.com/?p=230">received information about the client or meeting,</a> now here are some helpful tips to make your first impression with the client a lasting one:

<strong>Preparation</strong>:  If you’ve already received information regarding the meeting or appointment, it’s a good idea to read through the material to gather as much information as possible.  Arriving with this knowledge assures the client you have taken the time to understand why you’re there, and in stressful situations, this may help put them at ease.

<strong> </strong><strong>First Impressions</strong>: Even if you have a specific dress code from the agency you work for, professionalism will always be a requirement.  Unless otherwise specified, always show up in nothing less than business attire. Dressing like the professional you are indicates to clients that you take being their interpreter very seriously.

<strong> </strong><strong>“I am your interpreter:”</strong> With face-to-face interpreter meetings, take the initiative and introduce yourself as the client and provider’s interpreter.  If this is a returning assignment with the same provider, let the new client know that you’ll be present for the entire meeting or appointment.  Advise the client that the conversation is confidential.  Let them know they will need to speak to the person they’re communicating with, and you will interpret what they are saying in first person.  If they start to speak to you directly in the beginning, gently guide them to voice themselves to the other party.

Remember: you do not need an elaborate way to introduce yourself.  The confidence in your abilities as a face to face interpreter will shine through the entire session. If yourself, or your business, is looking for a <a href="http://www.telelanguage.com/onsite-interpretation">professional and reputable interpreting service</a>, Telelanguage offers 2000 interpreters ready to speak in 200 languages. Now, for even faster service, download the <a href="https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/telelanguage-services/id630044808?mt=8">Telelanguage app for iPhone</a>, and connect to a live interpreter in just seconds!

<strong> </strong>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Over 2,000 expertly skilled certified interpreters!</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Call us today at </strong><a href="http://blog.telelanguage.com/face-to-face-interpreters-how-to-make-a-good-first-impression/888-983-5352"><strong>888-983-5352</strong></a><strong> </strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Providing quality and expert interpretations telephonically or face to face!</em></p>]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>Telelanguage at the 80th Annual APCO Conference and Expo</title>
		<link>http://telelanguage.com/telelanguage-80th-annual-apco-conference-expo/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 23 Aug 2016 16:45:55 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://telelanguage.com/?p=2439</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[The <a href="https://www.apcointl.org/index.php">Association of Public-Safety Communications</a> held its 80th annual Conference and Expo August 3-6th in New Orleans, LA. APCO International is not only the largest global organization lending support to public safety communication professionals, but it’s also the oldest. APCO promotes strength in public safety communication across global industries, ensuring they’re providing the highest levels of public safety communication resources in the world.

<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-2441" src="http://telelanguage.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/08/Telelanguage-at-the-80th-Annual-APCO-Conference-and-Expo.png" alt="Telelanguage at the 80th Annual APCO Conference and Expo" width="298" height="180" />

Telelanguage joined the APCO Conference and Expo with a booth demonstrating how interpreter services are a beneficial asset to the public safety communications community, and will help expedite different situations should language barriers arise. With a live telephonic or face to face interpreter, both you and the person you’re trying to communicate will gain full understanding of one another in critical moments. In the matter of public safety communication, relying on Telelanguage for fast connections and expert service will guarantee that no matter what the situation may be, accuracy with our superior trained interpreters can be trusted.

To find out more about why Telelanguage is the leading provider of telephonic interpretation service, simply <a href="http://www.telelanguage.com/">visit our website</a>, or call us at: <a href="http://blog.telelanguage.com/telelanguage-at-the-80th-annual-apco-conference-and-expo/888-983-5352">888-983-5352</a>.  For your convenience, we’ve created an <a href="https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/telelanguage-services/id630044808?mt=8">app for iPhone</a>, which will connect you to a live interpreter in just seconds. With a team of over 2000 certified interpreter ready to speak in 200 languages, Telelanguage is available 24 hours a day, 7 days a week, 365 days a year.

&nbsp;]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>How to Prepare For Your Interpreter’s Arrival</title>
		<link>http://telelanguage.com/how-to-prepare-for-your-interpreters-arrival/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 23 Aug 2016 16:45:26 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://telelanguage.com/?p=2442</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-2554" src="http://telelanguage.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/08/Blog_How-to-prepare-for-int.jpg" alt="Alt=&quot;prepare-for-your-interpreter&quot;" width="1140" height="505" />If you’re in a global business that requires frequent meetings and conferences with associates and clients, it’s possible you’ve had to contact a <a href="http://www.telelanguage.com/">reliable interpreter service provider</a> for assistance.   We’ve given you <a href="http://blog.telelanguage.com/?p=178">6 helpful tips for working with an interpreter</a>, but it’s also important to know <strong><em>how to prepare for your interpreter's arrival</em></strong>.

<strong>Review the content</strong> – If you’re going into a conference or a meeting where your clients or audience may not speak your language, review the context of the material you’re going to cover, see if you’ve included regional dialect or idioms that may not be as easily interpreted. Adjusting the verbiage and being conscious of what will be interpreted to the non-language speaking audience will simplify the process for the interpreter.

<strong>Inform the interpreter</strong> – Fill the interpreter in on the content of the meeting. If you have the opportunity, email the agenda, notes, speech, or content the day before. Are you using visuals? Make the interpreter aware of your presentation, explaining the visual tools you’ll be using. This gives the interpreter direction and allows them to better prepare.

<strong>Meet the interpreter</strong> – It’s always a good idea to meet and touch base with the interpreter before the meeting or conference. The pre-meeting is a good time to notify them of any last minute changes (if any). Discuss and answer questions the interpreter may have regarding the material. If there’s terminology that shouldn’t be changed to keep the integrity of the content, let them know.

<strong>Last minute tips</strong>: Keep your pacing at a normal speed, avoid speaking in too many sentences at once. Remember to pause after each thought to allow for the interpreter to do their job. Speak directly to your audience, even if they do not speak your language. Feedback or questions from clients or an audience will be directed towards you, so remember to answer the person back directly. The interpreter is to be a neutral presence, and is not take your place leading the meeting or conference, nor are they to answer questions for you.

If you’ve prepared for a meeting or conference, then your next step is to contact a professional interpreter service to schedule an <a href="http://www.telelanguage.com/onsite-interpretation">on-site interpretation service</a>. With over 22 years in the language industry, Telelanguage offers over 2,000 interpreters and 200 languages. Scheduling an appointment is a simple, seamless process. Contact us 24 hours a day, 7 days a week, 365 days a year.

<strong> </strong>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Over 2,000 knowledgeable and expert certified interpreters!</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Call us today at </strong><a href="http://blog.telelanguage.com/how-to-prepare-for-your-interpreters-arrival/888-983-5352"><strong>888-983-5352</strong></a><strong> </strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Providing quality and expert face to face interpretations!</em></p>]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>What Does a Conference Interpreter Do?</title>
		<link>http://telelanguage.com/what-does-a-conference-interpreter-do/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 23 Aug 2016 16:47:18 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://telelanguage.com/?p=2446</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[If you’ve attended an international or professional seminar, summit, or conference, you may have noticed a conference interpreter present.  <a href="http://www.telelanguage.com/telephonic-interpretation/industrieswesupport">Conference interpreting</a> is a specialized skill which allows communication between the speaker and a group of audience members. Conference interpreters are tasked with listening to the context of what the speaker is saying, and relaying it back accurately in the target language, while preserving the integrity of the message. There are different types of conference interpreting, and different skill sets are needed depending on each one.

There are typically two styles interpreters will use to  deliver the speaker’s message back to an audience: <em>simultaneous</em> and <em>consecutive</em>. Consecutive means an interpreter listens to the speaker for a few sentences, and then will wait until the speaker pauses to begin relaying information back in the target language. These interpreters are sometimes located off to the side of a group that does not speak the language, and will quietly convey the content when the speaker breaks between sentences.  Simultaneous interpretations happen in real time. As the speaker is talking, the conference interpreter is relaying the content to an audience at the same time. Traditionally, these types of interpretations call for the interpreter to be in a booth speaking into a microphone with the audience members wearing headphones.

When choosing a conference interpreter, professionalism, experience, and skill will play a major role in your decision.  At <a href="http://www.telelanguage.com/">Telelanguage</a>, we pride ourselves with providing over 2,000 professional interpreters ready to speak in over 200 languages, 365 days a year. On the spot interpreters are able to arrive approximately 30 minutes from the original request, and for even faster service, our <a href="https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/telelanguage-services/id630044808?mt=8">app for iPhone </a> will connect you telephonically to an interpreter in just seconds.

<strong> </strong>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Schedule an interpreter for your next conference!</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Call us today at </strong><a href="http://blog.telelanguage.com/what-does-a-conference-interpreter-do/888-983-5352"><strong>888-983-5352</strong></a><strong> </strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Providing quality and expert interpretations telephonically or face to face!</em></p>]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>The Importance of Certified Medical and Health Care Interpreters</title>
		<link>http://telelanguage.com/the-role-of-medical-and-health-care-interpreters/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 23 Aug 2016 16:48:06 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://telelanguage.com/?p=2449</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[Across the nation, <a href="http://krcu.org/post/bridging-language-gap-medical-interpreters#.VQzMnyxX2mM.twitter via @krcufm">certified health care interpreters are in extreme demand</a>. Most medical and health care practices provide patients with the invaluable service from a <a href="http://www.telelanguage.com/">certified medical or health care interpreter</a>.  Certified interpreters are present for admittance, consultations, exams, and patient to health care provider appointments. Just as the interpreter is providing understanding to the patient, they are also relaying back pertinent information, like the patient’s current condition, and questions for the doctor.  Not only do these interpreters turn over the information at a fast rate, they also must practice being calm during stressful and emotionally charged emergency situations.

An interpreter’s job doesn’t stop at the medical or health care facility.  Oftentimes, the interpreter may be needed at a patient’s home, rehabilitation center, hospital, medical or healthcare facility.  In some cases, the interpreter will assist the doctor with patient follow-ups, or helping the patient fill out paperwork after appointments or exams.

Medical and health care interpreters must have passed and obtained the state mandated certification to work in such facilities.  Certified medical interpreters never cease in their learning and training as the certifications must be updated every few years. The certification process further qualifies that the interpreter is fit for servicing the medical and health care field, and is recognized by the state that they have met and surpassed all requirements.

Unfortunately, some providers do not offer medical or health care interpreters due to state or private funding constraints. When that happens, it’s important to make sure you’ve found <a href="http://blog.telelanguage.com/?p=212">a reliable interpreter</a> to accompany you or a family member to appointments.  If you’re in need of a certified healthcare or medical interpreter, Telelanguage offers <a href="http://www.telelanguage.com/onsite-interpretation">on the spot interpreters</a> that are able to be present within 30 minutes. Have an urgent or emergency situation and need an interpreter’s assistance within seconds? Download our <a href="https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/telelanguage-services/id630044808?mt=8">free app for iPhone here</a>, and reach any of our 2000 interpreters ready to speak in over 200 languages.

<strong> </strong>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Certified medical interpreters ready to speak in 200 languages!</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Call us today at </strong><a href="http://blog.telelanguage.com/the-role-of-medical-and-health-care-interpreters/888-983-5352"><strong>888-983-5352</strong></a><strong> </strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Quality and expert interpretations for your medical appointments telephonically </em><em>or face to face!</em></p>]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>How Do I Become an Interpreter?</title>
		<link>http://telelanguage.com/what-does-it-take-to-become-an-interpreter/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 23 Aug 2016 16:48:12 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://telelanguage.com/?p=2450</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[Can you imagine being in a meeting and not understanding what’s being said? Or how about being at a doctor’s office without having a clear comprehension of the prognosis?  The demand for the <a href="http://money.cnn.com/2013/10/30/news/economy/job-skills-foreign-language/"> hottest job skill</a> does not look to be slowing down anytime soon. The interpreter has become an integral asset wherever foreign languages are spoken and need to be converted to your own. Do you have an affinity for languages, and are thinking of a career move? We have broken down the steps for<strong><em> what it takes to become an interpreter</em></strong>:

<strong>Education and Language Proficiency</strong>: The most important factor to become an interpreter is education and sharp language skills. In the United States, typically you’ll need at least a Bachelor’s Degree. Most Universities will have courses designed to progress learning and skill in the field of interpretation. Along with native-speaking experience in your own language, you will need to be proficient in the desired second (or third) language as well. If you don’t have solid grasp of the language, you will need to take additional language courses.

<strong>Area of Specialization:</strong> With so many different career paths available to interpreters, choosing an area of specialization will determine your next course of action. There are several industries that depend on interpreters on a daily basis: Health care and emergency 9-1-1, judicial, educational, retail and consumer, and travel.  Each industry requires different criteria in order to excel.

<strong> </strong><strong>Certification</strong>: Some industries, like healthcare and judicial, require additional certifications to become an interpreter. It is important to obtain these certifications and keep them current. An interpreter that has been certified will be able to present certifications as confirmation that they are compliant with all current policies and procedures.

Interpreting is a profession in which you never stop learning.  Being the link between languages and providing understanding is what the interpreter aims to do. If you’re looking for a reliable service with <strong><em>experienced and certified interpreters</em></strong>, <a href="http://www.telelanguage.com/">Telelanguage interpreters</a> have acquired all of the above training and certifications. We have over 2000 interpreters ready to speak in over 200 languages, and are conveniently accessible whether telephonically, or on the spot. For an even faster connection to our interpreters, we’ve created a <a href="https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/telelanguage-services/id630044808?mt=8">breakthrough app for iPhone</a>, which allows you to reach an interpreter within seconds.

&nbsp;
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Professional and certified interpreters are ready to speak in just seconds!</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Call us today at </strong><a href="http://blog.telelanguage.com/what-does-it-take-to-become-an-interpreter/888-983-5352"><strong>888-983-5352</strong></a><strong> </strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Providing quality and expert interpretations face to face, call to set up an appointment!</em></p>]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>Need a Reliable Last Minute Interpreter For Your Meeting or Appointment?</title>
		<link>http://telelanguage.com/need-a-reliable-last-minute-interpreter-for-your-meeting-or-appointment/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 23 Aug 2016 16:49:08 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://telelanguage.com/?p=2454</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[Whether for work or personal, last minute meetings and appointments are bound to happen. When those meetings involve communication with someone that doesn’t speak your language, how do you find an interpreter in a short amount of time? Here are some tips for <a href="http://www.telelanguage.com/">finding a last minute interpreter</a>:

<strong> </strong><strong>Research</strong> – A quick search can provide several results, but how will you know which interpreting service best fits your needs? What you’re looking for in an interpreter is not only professionalism but acquired skills and proficiency in the area you desire. If you need the interpreter for medical or legal appointments, business meetings or conferences, make sure the service provides interpreters have been certified, and that the certifications are current.

<strong>Certifications</strong> – Why should it matter if an interpreter is certified? Certifications are important as they establish the interpreter took the necessary extra steps to master not only the language but is equipped with knowledge and experience in the chosen field to better assist you. Certifications also show that the interpreter complies with national practice standards.

<strong> </strong><strong>Experience and Reliability</strong> – A service that has a track record that goes back for years is a good sign that the interpreter service has established roots in the industry.  A reflection of years of service is reliability.  With years of combined experience and reliability comes consistent quality and professionalism.

<strong> </strong><strong>Positive Feedback</strong> – As always, check for feedback, see what others have said about using the interpreter service. If a service has interpreters that have been certified and have proven experience and reliability, satisfied customers and clients will stand behind them.

If you find yourself in need of a last minute interpreter, <a href="http://www.telelanguage.com/onsite-interpretation">Telelanguage</a> offers not only urgent over the phone responses, but can be on site within 30 minutes of the initial request. In addition to telephonic and on the spot interpreters, this <a href="https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/telelanguage-services/id630044808?mt=8">free to download app for iPhone</a> connects you to an interpreter in just seconds. Telelanguage has over 20 years in the industry backing them up, with a team of over 2000 interpreters ready to speak in over 200 languages.

<strong> </strong>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Reliable and certified interpreters ready to speak in over 200 languages!</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Call us today at </strong><a href="http://blog.telelanguage.com/need-a-reliable-last-minute-interpreter-for-your-meeting-or-appointment/888-983-5352"><strong>888-983-5352</strong></a><strong> </strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Providing quality and expert telephonic interpretations, call to set up an appointment!</em></p>]]></content:encoded>

		<title>Retail, Consumer, and Hospitality Interpreters</title>
		<link>http://telelanguage.com/retail-consumer-hospitality-interpreters/</link>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://telelanguage.com/?p=2457</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[In a fast-paced global business world, communication and presentation leads to success.  When it comes to retail, consumer, and hospitality industries, information travels rapidly, making universal understanding necessary. <a href="http://www.telelanguage.com/telephonic-interpretation/industrieswesupport">Retail, consumer, and hospitality interpreters</a> are a major asset to any of these industry sectors. Inter-personal relations with clients make interpreters a valuable asset, and having one present helps cultivate that relationship between businesses and the public.  Here’s how an interpreter’s role factors into these below industries to booster target reach and further client relations:

<strong>Retail and Consumer Industry</strong>– Think retail is only about fashion? Think again: The retail and consumer industry sector contains everything from grocery stores, food/beverage products, hotels, retail merchandising, retail apparel, and more.  Retail industries make a conscious effort to be seen understood on a global level with branding and marketing.  Interpreters offer deep understanding and knowledge of a language’s culture, providing interpretations that make sense to the native tongue.

<strong> </strong><strong>Hospitality Industry</strong> – If you’ve traveled to other countries for business, you understand how important hospitality interpreters are. For arriving at airports, help getting you to hotel accommodations, navigating the city and joining you for business engagements, interpreters are equipped with knowledge of the local culture, enabling them to break through language barriers. These hospitality interpreters can also double as guides, making discovering the local shops, food and tourist attractions a smooth experience.

For these fast paced environments, it’s important that the interpreter has been trained to react and think quickly and speak accurately. <a href="http://www.telelanguage.com/">Telelanguage </a>offers professional certified and skilled interpreters that are proficient in over 200 languages. Telelanguage’s interpreters are available 24 hours a day, 7 days a week.

	<item>
		<title>Tips For Working With a Business Interpreter</title>
		<link>http://telelanguage.com/tips-working-business-interpreter/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 23 Aug 2016 16:51:51 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://telelanguage.com/?p=2459</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[Business globalization has become increasingly popular, with companies expanding their clientele and customers across the world.  Now more than ever, there’s a need for interpreters to be present in meetings and conferences.  If you’re a business that wishes to expand communication, here’s some helpful tips for bringing a <a href="http://www.telelanguage.com/">professional business interpreter in the office</a>:

Contact a professional service:  Before welcoming an interpreter into your place of business, it’s best to do your due diligence and research a reputable company.  Choose a <a href="http://telelanguage.com/onsite-interpretation">reliable interpreting service</a> that provides on the spot interpreters in the desired language.  Make sure the interpreter is a qualified business interpreter, and has current certifications.

<strong> </strong><strong>Professional environment</strong>:  We depend on the interpreter to provide rapid on the spot interpretations, and their performance will benefit greatly when the environment of the office is professional. The meeting place should be void of distractions, making focusing easier for your interpreter.

<strong> </strong><strong>Preparation before meetings</strong>:  Providing your interpreter with documents or resource materials of what subject matter will be covered beforehand will help gain familiarity of the topic. Be sure to fill the interpreter in on the projected direction of the meeting, the meeting’s content, and any other information that will aid the interpreter in understanding what the meeting’s ultimate goal is.

<strong>Communicate directly with the person/people you’re speaking with</strong>: An interpreter’s presence is meant to be neutral. Speak directly to your target audience, allowing the interpreter to properly and effectively communicate with them in their language. Interpreters in a business setting are to not be engaged, instead they are there to solely provide understanding.

Whether you are looking for an interpreter to sit in on meetings, or to have one for a specific business event, make sure the interpreter comes from an <a href="http://www.telelanguage.com/">accredited interpretation service provider</a>. If you need help choosing an interpreter for your specific needs, <a href="http://www.telelanguage.com/telephonic-interpretation/industrieswesupport">Telelanguage </a>understands that each situation is unique, and will provide a certified business interpreter that will be an excellent fit. Interpreters at Telelanguage can arrive to an on the spot location in as little as 30 minutes from the time of request should you have an immediate need.

<strong> </strong>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Contact certified interpreters for your next business meeting!</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Call us today at </strong><a href="http://blog.telelanguage.com/tips-for-working-with-a-business-interpreter/888-983-5352"><strong>888-983-5352</strong></a><strong> </strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Providing quality and expert interpretations face to face, call to set up an appointment!</em></p>]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>Common Myths About Interpreters</title>
		<link>http://telelanguage.com/common-myths-interpreters/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 23 Aug 2016 16:52:40 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://telelanguage.com/?p=2461</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[In situations where two parties or individuals need to understand each other, an interpreter is going to be the most valuable asset.  We’ve touched on one of the biggest myths in the past: <a href="http://blog.telelanguage.com/?p=64">Bilingual speakers are not necessarily interpreters</a>, and now we’d like to eliminate a few more common myths about interpreting:

<strong><em>Myth: My bilingual child/family member/friend can attend medical appointments with me, I don’t need an interpreter:</em></strong>

Truth: While you might get by bringing along a second language speaker to grasp the general idea, critical information will be discussed that may contain complex terminology.  Unless a person has gone through extensive training to understand these terms, they will not know how to accurately describe the content of what was said. It’s best that a certified medical interpreter is present for not only accuracy, but peace of mind that every detail has been correctly explained to ensure understanding.

<strong><em> </em></strong><strong><em>Myth: I speak a second language, I’m an interpreter!</em></strong>

Truth: Fluency in your native language must be beyond a conversational level in order to be an interpreter. Being able to speak a second or third language is a major part of the requirement, but the knowledge and vocabulary needed to accurately relay information from one person to another is a mastered skill.  Depending on your level of expertise in a language, a person interested in becoming an interpreter may need to take language classes before they can move forward with courses of specialized training in the fields they desire.  Interpreters must also keep their certifications current as new terms, procedures, and regional colloquialisms are constantly being infused into our languages.

<strong><em> </em></strong><strong><em>Myth: Having an interpreter means they will answer the questions from the person I’m trying to communicate with for me:</em></strong>

Truth:  An interpreter’s goal is to provide understanding between yourself and the person you’re trying to communicate with. An interpreter is a neutral presence and is never to answer questions for you.  Your eye contact and conversation should transpire between yourself and the other person, with the interpreter only engaging when delivering the content of the conversation.

<strong><em> </em></strong><strong><em>Myth: An interpreter can interpret for ANY industry:</em></strong>

Truth: Requirements for interpreting vary in different industries. UN interpreters will have different certifications and requirements than staff interpreters in a business setting.  If an individual is looking to become an interpreter for the medical or judicial industries, the criteria will also be drastically different. Depending on which industry an individual chooses, training to become an interpreter may even take years before they’re able to provide service.

Having a dedicated interpreter available within seconds is exactly what ensures confidence when choosing a provider for your interpretation needs. Choosing a reliable service with not only certified interpreters, but are available 24 hours a day, 7 days a week is important when you’re in a situation that requires one. At <a href="http://www.telelanguage.com/">Telelanguage</a>, our certified and skilled interpreters are ready to speak for you wherever you’re at in the world, 365 days a year.

&nbsp;
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Connect in seconds to one of 2000 telephonic certified interpreters!</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Call us today at </strong><a href="http://blog.telelanguage.com/common-myths-about-interpreters/888-983-5352"><strong>888-983-5352</strong></a><strong> </strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Providing quality and expert interpretations over the phone or face to face 24/7/365!</em></p>]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>3 Ways Certified Interpreters Help Everyday Situations</title>
		<link>http://telelanguage.com/3-different-ways-interpreters-help-everyday-situations/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 23 Aug 2016 16:53:19 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://telelanguage.com/?p=2463</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[When we think of interpreters, we immediately think of medical, conference, or legal situations. Although interpreters are most commonly used for these cases, here are some other ways a <a href="http://www.telelanguage.com/">certified interpreter</a> can help offer assistance:

<strong> </strong><strong>In the office</strong>– Have you ever had to conduct an interview, or had a lengthy meeting with a business associate that does not speak your language?  Certified interpreters are highly trained to be able to be professionally presentable, and help get your important messages across in the appointment.

<strong>At home</strong>– Some other ways certified interpreters can be a huge benefit are right in your own home. If you live with or have a relative that’s a Limited English Speaker, an on the spot interpreter will assist with them appointments, like with the cable company or an internet provider. If a problem arises where the LES need to speak to a landlord, they can always rely on an interpreter to help them both on the spot or telephonically.

<strong> </strong><strong>Education</strong> – For students enrolling or transferring to different schools whose parents may not speak the language, having an interpreter assist with filling out forms and paperwork for enrollment will make the transition process a smooth one. Parent-teacher conferences are also an opportunity to have an on the spot interpreter come in and provide understanding to help relay critical information about the student’s education.

For any situation you may encounter, a certified interpreter will be able to meet you either on the spot or over the phone, and is available 24 hours a day, 7 days a week. For even faster connections, Telelanguage has created a <a href="https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/telelanguage-services/id630044808?mt=8">breakthrough app for iPhone</a> that’s free to download, and you’ll be connected to a live interpreter ready to speak your language in just seconds.

<strong> </strong>

	<item>
		<title>The Difference Between Interpreters and Translators</title>
		<link>http://telelanguage.com/difference-interpreter-translator/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 23 Aug 2016 16:54:21 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://telelanguage.com/?p=2465</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[Have you found yourself in a situation where you need to communicate with someone else, but don’t know if you need an interpreter or a translator? Interpreters and translators may seem as if they’re one in the same, one might even say they’ve had something translated after speaking to an interpreter, and vice versa.  If both have the ability to take languages and decipher them in a way that leads to understanding, then <strong>what’s the difference between interpreters and translators</strong>?

Both translators and interpreters must have a significant amount of cultural awareness, knowledge of regional dialects, and a grasp of colloquialisms from those regions in order to properly and accurately deliver the intended message. Though both interpreters and translators must have a mastery of both the target language and the language they are interpreting or translating into, there are different skill sets and requirements for each field.

The first major difference is that Interpreters operate orally, while translators deliver their work in a written format.  What also sets interpreters and translators apart is their work environments.  You will find interpreters in situations where they are called to be at a physical location, like a courthouse or a hospital. Translators are sometimes involved in projects that do not require being in a setting with the party that requires the translation, such as translating text in novels and books, or websites.

Translators will take the source text they need to translate, and use a variety of resources to help them accurately transpose the text into the target language. In some instances, they will need to be subject matter experts in order to accurately translate specific text. Translators need to have a cultural understanding of the target language, and they  typically tend to be native speakers. Translators only translate into one direction: From the source material to the target language.

Unlike a translator, an interpreter must be able to translate in two directions: From the source language to the target language, and then from the target language back to the source language. This is done live, either on the spot or telephonic, and can be done consecutively or simultaneously. Consecutive interpretations means the speaker is able to deliver a few sentences at a time, and an interpreter will relay them to the recipient after a thought has been completed. Simultaneous interpretation requires an interpreter to listen and deliver the content of the speaker while the speaker is still speaking. Because of these two types of methods, an interpreter would have gone through extensive qualifying testing, and if the interpreter is being used in a medical or judicial setting, extra certifications are needed.
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Professional telephonic certified interpreters ready to connect in just seconds!</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Call us today at </strong><a href="http://blog.telelanguage.com/the-difference-between-an-interpreter-and-a-translator/888-983-5352"><strong>888-983-5352</strong></a><strong> </strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Providing quality and expert interpretations over the phone or face to face 24/7/365!</em></p>]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>Interpreters and Their Role in the Emergency 9-1-1 Industry</title>
		<link>http://telelanguage.com/interpreters-and-their-role-in-the-emergency-9-1-1-industry/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 23 Aug 2016 16:55:05 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://telelanguage.com/?p=2467</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[If you or a loved one has ever needed medical attention, you understand how important it is to communicate precise information about the situation.  In some cases, misunderstandings could be <a href="http://www.oregonlive.com/portland/index.ssf/2014/04/spanish_interpreter_botched_9-.html">a matter of life or death</a>.  Emergencies happen constantly, and we depend heavily on our 9-1-1 operators in the United States to get us the urgent help we need.  What happens if you don’t speak the English language when you need to dial 9-1-1, and how would you get assistance from a <a href="http://www.telelanguage.com/">certified interpreter</a>?

In the United States, 9-1-1 operators are trained to handle inbound callers that might not speak English.  It’s suggested that non-English speakers be able to specify in English which language they speak.   This way, an operator will be able to get the correct language speaker on the line. Although a 9-1-1 operator may speak the language of the caller, it’s required that a <a href="http://www.telelanguage.com/telephonic-interpretation/industrieswesupport">certified interpreter</a>  joins the call to ensure accuracy.  Once the 9-1-1 operator is able to determine which language the caller speaks, the certified interpreter will be connected the call in a matter of moments.

Interpreters that are connected to these emergency lines have gone through demanding testing to achieve this <a href="http://www.certifiedmedicalinterpreters.org/prerequisites">level of certification</a>.  They are able to rapidly receive information in chaotic situations, and then deliver it accurately back to the 9-1-1 operator.  Because of this, we can feel confident that our loved ones will always get the assistance they need.

Are you concerned that your limited English or second language speaker in your home will encounter an emergency and may not know how to communicate in English? Here are some general tips to ensure they’ll be able to react while you’re away:

<strong>Learn a basic phrase</strong>: As previously stated, it helps the 9-1-1 operator to know which language the caller speaks.  Have the limited English or second language person learn a basic phrase to utilize should an emergency arise, and then periodically practice it.

<strong>Written phrases</strong>:  Place a note card with a common phrase or two of what to say once they’ve dialed 9-1-1 in a central location as a reference.

For other situations that may not be a 9-1-1 emergency, having a practical and convenient way to <strong>connect to a live interpreter</strong> will reduce stress and put a non-English speaker at ease.   Telelanguage provides a<a href="https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/telelanguage-services/id630044808?mt=8"> free to download app for iPhone</a> that’ll connect your loved one to an interpreter in a matter of seconds.  With 2,000 interpreters knowledgeable in 200 languages, Telelanguage is ready to speak your language 24 hours a day, 7 days a week, wherever you are.
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong> </strong><strong>
9-1-1 emergency certified interpreters ready to connect in just seconds!</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Call us today at </strong><a href="http://blog.telelanguage.com/interpreters-and-their-role-in-the-emergency-9-1-1-industry/888-983-5352"><strong>888-983-5352</strong></a><strong> </strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Providing quality and expert interpretations over the phone 24/7/365!</em></p>]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>6 Tips for Working with a Live Interpreter</title>
		<link>http://telelanguage.com/6-tips-working-live-interpreter/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 23 Aug 2016 16:55:31 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://telelanguage.com/?p=2469</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-2520" src="http://telelanguage.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/08/Blog_6-Tips-for-Working-wit.jpg" alt="Alt=&quot;6-Tips-for-Working-with-live-interpreter&quot;" width="1140" height="505" />

When faced with a situation that involves dependency on a professional <a href="http://www.telelanguage.com/onsite-interpretation">on the spot interpreter</a>, there are a few things to keep in mind to ensure the session is beneficial to both parties. A skilled live interpreter listens, comprehends, and delivers a conversation to the recipient in their language, and vice versa. For this reason, it’s important that the interpreter you’re working with is fluent in both your language and the language of the person you need to communicate with.

Here are a few tips that’ll make your first time with a professional interpreter a smooth one:

<strong>Make sure the interpreter is qualified</strong> – As mentioned above, understanding of the languages is one of the most important qualities an interpreter must possess. In addition to proficiency in languages, make sure your interpreter is up to date on their certifications. If you’re in need of a live interpreter for business or in the medical field, it’s crucial that they’re well versed in terminology or vocabulary that allows them to effectively receive and deliver vital information.

<strong> </strong><strong>Allow for enough time</strong> – Because there’s a potential for a conversation through an interpreter to take twice as long, plan out a sufficient amount of time for the entire process. This will eliminate the need to rush, and will result in good quality that’s critical when working with an interpreter.

<strong> </strong><strong>Speak clearly</strong> – Even though an interpreter may be trained to listen and comprehend what is said at a quick pace, it’s still important to speak clearly and slowly. If you are unclear, the interpreter will have to stop you to repeat what you say, delaying the translation process. Remember to pause after a thought is complete. If you’re in a group, make sure only one person speaks at a time.

<strong> </strong><strong>Choose your words wisely</strong> – Professional interpreters are knowledgeable of social cues, idioms, and other cultural phrases. However: Depending on the type of translation you need, such as in a business setting, you’ll want to make sure you are using phrases that speak to the professionalism of the company you’re representing. With that being said, try your best to avoid complex sentences that contain heavy amounts of slang. Use simple yet concise wording that will easily be translatable, making the process smooth and productive.

<strong>Listen to responses before speaking again</strong> – While an interpreter is delivering a translation to you, be careful to not interrupt. Listen to the entire string of sentences before responding. This will allow for the person you’re trying to communicate with to express their thought through the interpreter, and will prevent backtracking or re-explaining.

<strong> </strong><strong>Don’t rely on the interpreter to respond for you</strong> – Even when the simplest questions are asked, don’t rely on the interpreter to assume your answer, or answer for you on your behalf. A live interpreter is a neutral presence, and isn’t meant to be involved in the conversation other than the purpose of providing communication and understanding.

Some individuals may lean on family members or friends for communicating, but what happens when it’s imperative to relay medical, legal, or business information? It’s important that you are working with a professional live interpreter, as it’ll be the best way to avoid errors and misunderstandings. Whether for business, medical, or travel, Telelanguage offers 200 professional interpreters in over 2,000 languages, and are available 365 days a year. We offer both telephonic and on-location interpreters for any industry! <a href="http://www.telelanguage.com/">Contact us</a> to learn more!

<strong> </strong>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>LIVE certified interpreters ready to connect in just seconds!</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Call us today at </strong><a href="http://blog.telelanguage.com/6-tips-for-working-with-a-live-interpreter/888-983-5352"><strong>888-983-5352</strong></a><strong> </strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Providing quality and expert interpretations over the phone 24/7/365, or contact us to set up face to face appointments!</em></p>]]></content:encoded>
