	<item>
		<title>3 Useful Ways to Use the Telelanguage iPhone App at Home</title>
		<link>http://telelanguage.com/three-useful-ways-to-use-our-interpretation-iphone-app-at-home/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 23 Aug 2016 16:57:12 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://telelanguage.com/?p=2471</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<img class="here alignnone size-full wp-image-2514" src="http://telelanguage.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/08/Blog_3-useful-ways-to-use-i.jpg" alt="Alt=&quot;3 Useful Ways to use the Telelanguage iPhone App&quot;" width="1140" height="505" />

In the age of technology, there’s a phrase we’ve heard all too often: “<em>There’s an app for that</em>.” Although said humorously in situations where you actually wished you had an app for it, there is one that exists that is practical for key times you need immediate assistance with communication, the <strong>Telelanguage iPhone App.</strong>

<a href="https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/telelanguage-services/id630044808?mt=8">A brand new app for iPhone</a>, which is useful to worldwide travelers, is also extremely helpful in everyday life. Check out how having an interpreter in your pocket is useful while in your homeland:

In metropolitan cities where amazing melting pots of businesses have been established, you might find that some parts of town are heavily populated with language speakers that are not your own. Ordering at restaurants or speaking to people in shops can be made into a unique experience when you are able to communicate with them. When you’re able to understand the language, you might also be surprised to learn more about your community, and the people that live there.

For those of us that have families overseas, having them come to town is a joyous occasion. For some, work or education obligations may cause periods of time where those family members are not close by. When we have to leave our loved ones in a city they aren’t familiar with, an app that puts an interpreter, in their hands will ease the stress of worrying if they’re able to communicate without you. Do you have family visiting you from a foreign country, and you’re not familiar with their language? Take this opportunity to be able to speak to them, and connect to them in a way you’ve never been able to before via the Telelanguage iPhone App.

We might have family members that live with us whose native language differs from yours, so an interpreter that is certified and knowledgeable of medical terminology is a tremendous asset should that family member fall ill. What’s important is making sure the correct information is being relayed from the patient to the doctor, which makes an app that quickly connects you to a live interpreter so important. In a matter of mere seconds, you can rest easy that you’re getting the proper information, and the medical staff will be able to accurately tend to your loved one.

Having a live telephonic language interpreter that you can reach in a matter of seconds is useful for any situation, whether traveling abroad, or right where you live. The Telelanguage iPhone App is available for free <a href="https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/telelanguage-services/id630044808?mt=8">right here</a>. Download it now, and challenge yourself to get more involved in your own community!

&nbsp;
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Professional telephonic certified interpreters ready to connect in just seconds!</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Call us today at </strong><a href="http://blog.telelanguage.com/three-useful-ways-to-use-our-interpretation-iphone-app-at-home/888-983-5352"><strong>888-983-5352</strong></a><strong> </strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Providing quality and expert interpretations over the phone 24/7/365, or contact us to set up face to face appointments!</em></p>]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>Why Certain Industries Need to Provide Interpreter Services</title>
		<link>http://telelanguage.com/why-certain-industries-need-to-provide-interpreter-services/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 23 Aug 2016 16:58:48 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://telelanguage.com/?p=2474</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-2517" src="http://telelanguage.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/08/Blog_Certain-Industries-Nee.jpg" alt="Certain-Industries-Nee" width="1140" height="505" />

We’re an <strong>Interpreter Services</strong> company. We have a little insight into the industries that either, use our services regularly, or are in need of expanded use of interpreter services. With that in mind, we decided to put together of list of these industries and why it’s so important that they make interpreter services available. It’s not all inclusive — but it’s a start.
<ol>
 	<li><strong> Medical</strong>— This is a given. People face life and death situations when it comes to their health, so they need to be able to communicate their needs, questions, and concerns with those providing services.<strong> </strong></li>
</ol>
<ol start="2">
 	<li><strong> Emergency</strong>— Anyone can be impacted by an emergency at any given time. First responders have no clue what they are going to come across when they come into the fold. Given the diverse society we live in, it’s not too far-fetched that an individual might speak a different language. Access to interpreter services is crucial in such situations.</li>
</ol>
<ol start="3">
 	<li><strong>Legal </strong>— When it comes to legal issues, there is a lot on the line. From the initial conversation with an attorney to trial, it’s important that all parties be able to understand everything that is said. As such, interpreter services in the legal realm are imperative.<strong> </strong></li>
</ol>
<ol start="4">
 	<li><strong> Customer Service </strong>(across industries) — When you have a problem, you want to be able to get the problem resolved. And if a company provides you with a number to call, you also want to be able to communicate with the person on the other end of the phone. Companies never know what language their end users may speak, so it’s important to be prepared to provide interpreter services to individuals whose language doesn’t match that of the representative on the other end of the phone.</li>
</ol>
Stay tuned. We’ll continue this list with four more industries in need of providing interpreter services. Are we on track so far?

Follow us on <a href="http://twitter.com/Telelanguage">Twitter</a> and like us on <a href="http://www.facebook.com/telelanguageinc">Facebook</a> to stay up-to-date on the latest industry news!]]></content:encoded>

		<title>5 Tips for Using a Telephone Interpreter in a Healthcare Setting</title>
		<link>http://telelanguage.com/using-telephone-interpreter-in-healthcare/</link>
		<pubDate>Thu, 27 Oct 2016 09:52:59 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[kimberlyscamman]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://telelanguage.com/?p=2712</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[Using a <strong>telephone interpreter</strong> in healthcare can be challenging if you don’t understand best practices. It’s important to know how to make your time with a professional telephone interpreter effective and meaningful for your limited-English proficient (LEP) patients.

<span style="font-weight: 400;">When using interpreters in healthcare settings, always make sure they are a certified medical interpreter. Why certified? </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Recent Anti-Discrimination</span> <a href="http://www.cmelearning.com/new-2016-aca-rules-significantly-affect-the-law-of-language-access/"><span style="font-weight: 400;">changes to the Affordable Care Act (ACA)</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> require that </span><i>hospitals, health plans, clinics, nursing homes, physicians, and other providers must offer “qualified interpreters” to Limited English Proficient patients.</i>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">For more information on </span><b>understanding the Affordable Care Act (ACA)</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">, download our free </span><a href="http://telelanguage.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/Telelanguage-supports-new-National-Health-Law.pdf"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Language Access Checklist</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">. </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">While these changes are necessary for providing quality care to LEP Patients, healthcare professionals often struggle with how to use a professional interpreter effectively. The good news? You don’t have to struggle when using professional phone interpreters in healthcare settings! As a leading provider of </span><a href="http://telelanguage.com/the-role-of-medical-and-health-care-interpreters/"><span style="font-weight: 400;">certified medical interpreters</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">, we understand where problems can arise and have come up with 5 simple tips for using a telephone interpreter for LEP patients in a healthcare environment.   </span>
<span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span>
<h2>Tips for Using a Telephone Interpreter in Healthcare</h2>
<span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><b>1. Begin the conversation by allowing interpreters to introduce themselves and provide their interpreter identification number.</b><b>
</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Professional interpreters will give a brief introduction at the beginning of your call in the patient’s language. This introduction consists of identifying themselves as a professional interpreter, explaining their role as a channel for communication, clarifying with the patient that they will interpret everything they say, and giving their Identification number.</span>

<i><span style="font-weight: 400;">NOTE:</span></i><span style="font-weight: 400;"> It is important to write down the interpreter identification number in the patient’s file or patient notes for continuity and tracking.</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><b>2. Provide the interpreter with brief context.</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Briefly explain the purpose of the call. This will ensure that the interpreter will be able to provide an appropriate tone for the situation. For example, a routine follow-up would naturally have a different tone than a very serious or immediate situation. </span>

&nbsp;

<b>3. Speak to your patient (not to the interpreter).</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Speak to your patient directly as if the interpreter was not present. Making eye contact with your patient (not at the phone - or screen if using </span><a href="http://telelanguage.com/services/video-remote-interpretation/"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Video Remote Interpreting</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">) and speaking in the first person will bring simplicity, conciseness, and a natural flow to the conversation. Not only will this ensure accuracy on the healthcare side, but it will also help patients feel more comfortable and natural in the setting, allowing for a more accurate account or response from your LEP patient. </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">Example:</span></i><span style="font-weight: 400;"> “Tell Mr. Tao that we will require a blood test today.” </span>

<i><span style="font-weight: 400;">Suggestion:</span></i><span style="font-weight: 400;"> “Mr. Tao, we will require a blood test today.” </span>

&nbsp;

<b>4. Choose standard and formal speech. Avoid slang and colloquialisms.</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Common phrases for native English speakers like “feeling blue” or “let’s wrap up” may not translate effectively into another language. Using direct, uncomplicated language will reduce the chance of confusion that can arise due to cultural differences.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><b>5. Use complete and concise sentences. </b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Speaking to your patient in complete and concise sentences will simplify the message and maximize comprehension. Pausing briefly between your sentences will aid the phone interpreter in delivering the most straightforward message by not having to memorize paragraphs of speech at one time. </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">Example:</span></i><span style="font-weight: 400;"> “So, what I’m was thinking is that I’d like to start by going over your lab results if that sounds good to you?”</span>

<i><span style="font-weight: 400;">Suggestion:</span></i><span style="font-weight: 400;"> “I would like to explain your lab results, please.”</span>

<i><span style="font-weight: 400;">Tip:</span></i><span style="font-weight: 400;"> “Please” and “thank you” are relatively universal means of conveying politeness in different cultures. Using “please” and “thank you” can reduce filler words that may not translate well and will help your phone interpreter deliver the clearest message to your patient.</span>

&nbsp;

<span style="font-weight: 400;">These 5 tips for using telephone interpreters in healthcare are easy to implement and will maximize your time with your professional interpreter! Have you tried these tips? Let us know your experience in the comments below. </span>

&nbsp;
<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Certified medical interpreters ready to speak in 200 languages!</span></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Call us today at 888-983-5352 </span></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">Quality and expert interpretations for medical appointments are available telephonically, face to face, or by video remote!</span></i></p>]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>Who is a Qualified Interpreter Under Section 1557?</title>
		<link>http://telelanguage.com/qualified-interpreter-section-1557/</link>
		<pubDate>Wed, 02 Nov 2016 09:55:52 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[kimberlyscamman]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://telelanguage.com/?p=2757</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<span style="font-weight: 400;">Section 1557 of the Affordable Care Act (ACA) spotlights the importance of language services in hospitals and healthcare, adding requirements and specifically giving Limited English Proficient (LEP) patients the rights to a <strong>qualified interpreter</strong> in order to </span><a href="http://www.cqfluency.com/blog/need-know-section-1557-affordable-care-act/"><span style="font-weight: 400;">advance healthcare equality and reduce disparities in health care</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Medical interpreters fulfill an increasing need for quality language services in healthcare. Telelanguage is a well-known leader in promoting affordable access to healthcare interpretation quality through its accreditation, education and measurement programs. It is extremely important that providers be aware of these new regulations. We’ve compiled a Language Access Checklist regarding the National Health Law Program and Affordable Healthcare Act that provides recommendations to advocates to address the needs of LEP consumers in their health insurance marketplace:</span>

&nbsp;
<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">[DOWNLOAD the </span><strong><a href="http://telelanguage.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/Telelanguage-supports-new-National-Health-Law.pdf">National Health Law Program and Affordable Healthcare Act: Language Access Checklist</a></strong><span style="font-weight: 400;"><strong>.</strong>]</span></p>
&nbsp;

<span style="font-weight: 400;">An important change in the Department of Health and Human Resources (HRR) </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">ruling applies to the use and standard of interpreters for LEP patients. Formerly mandating “competent” interpreters</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"> (2003), the new ruling now requires “qualified” interpreters, meaning the use of a qualified interpreter should be considered the standard in healthcare for LEP patients.</span>

&nbsp;
<h3>What Does Limited English Proficient (LEP) Mean?</h3>
<span style="font-weight: 400;">A </span><a href="https://www.federalregister.gov/d/2016-11458"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Limited English Proficient</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Individual is defined by the Office for Civil Rights (OCR), Office of the Secretary, HHS as “an individual whose primary language for communication is not English” and “is considered an individual with limited English proficiency if the individual has a limited ability to read, write, speak or understand English.” </span>
<h3></h3>
&nbsp;
<h3>How Can Healthcare Providers Provide a Qualified Interpreter for LEP Patients?</h3>
<span style="font-weight: 400;">For compliance with Section 1557 of the Affordable Care Act (ACA) healthcare providers should consider healthcare and medical interpreters with the following qualifications:</span>

<strong>1.  <i><i>Interpreters</i></i><i><i> Should Adhere to a Code of Ethics</i></i></strong>

A trained and qualified interpreter in healthcare must adhere to ethical standards, such as client confidentiality.

<i><span style="font-weight: 400;"><strong>2.  Interpreters Should Have Formal Training and Testing</strong></span></i><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">The change for language interpreters from “competent” to “qualified” requires having a qualification. Simply using a bilingual or </span>multilingual person may not be considered “qualified” unless the individual has relevant training and proficiency testing to interpret.

<strong>3.  <i>Interpreters Should Be Recognized as Professional</i></strong>

HHS deters providers from reliance on bilingual staff (if their stated job duties do NOT include interpreting).

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Additionally, a </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">qualified <a href="http://www.cmelearning.com/new-2016-aca-rules-significantly-affect-the-law-of-language-access/">interpreter will have demonstrated</a></span><span style="font-weight: 400;"> proficiency in speaking and understanding both spoken English and at </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">least </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">one other spoken language</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"> and can interpret effectively, accurately, and impartially with LEP individuals in their primary </span>language using any necessary specialized vocabulary and phraseology.
<i><span style="font-weight: 400;">Telelanguage has 25 years experience providing language interpretation services for the healthcare industry. Our Telelanguage </span></i><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">Interpreter Certification Program</span></i><i><span style="font-weight: 400;"> (TICP) is a 120-hour training course combined with a 370-page training manual, exceeding the industry standard 30-hour training. In addition to TICP training, Telelanguage also provides a medical interpreter certification, requiring 120 Hours of Academic Medical Training &amp; Healthcare Interpreting Ethics, which is well above the </span></i><a href="http://www.certifiedmedicalinterpreters.org/"><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">National Board of Medical Interpreters</span></i></a><i><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Requirements.</span></i>

&nbsp;
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Certified medical interpreters ready to speak in 200 languages!</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">Contact us for <a href="http://telelanguage.com/contact-us/">special rates for section 1557 compliance</a>.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">Quality and expert interpretations for your medical appointments telephonically, face to face, or video remote!</span></i></p>]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>3 Benefits of Video Remote Interpreting (Infographic)</title>
		<link>http://telelanguage.com/video-remote-interpreting-infographic/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 08 Nov 2016 11:19:53 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[kimberlyscamman]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://telelanguage.com/?p=2791</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<span style="font-weight: 400;">Video Remote Interpreting (VRI) is at the forefront of language access technology. If you currently use language interpreting services, chances are that you have heard of this service, but you may be thinking, “What is it exactly, and how can it benefit my company or service?” As a </span><a href="http://www.telelanguage.com"><span style="font-weight: 400;">trusted language service provider</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> across multiple industries for the past 25 years, we know the importance of effective communication, and in this post, you will learn:</span>
<ol>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">What is Video Remote Interpreting (VRI)</span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Who can benefit from VRI Services; and</span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">3 key benefits of VRI  </span></li>
</ol>
&nbsp;
<h2>What is Video Remote Interpreting?</h2>
<b>Video remote interpreting</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> (</span><b>VRI</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">) is an on-demand</span> <a href="http://www.interpretereducation.org/specialization/vrs-vri/"><span style="font-weight: 400;">video telecommunication</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"> service</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> that uses devices such as web camera</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">s</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">, videophones or tablets over a high-speed internet connection to provide American Sign Language (ASL) or spoken language interpreting services. This is done through a remote or offsite interpreter while the English-speaking party and LEP individual are in the same location. A Video Remote interpreter</span>

&nbsp;
<h2>Who Can Benefit From Video Remote Interpreting Services?</h2>
<span style="font-weight: 400;">Video Remote Interpreting is the perfect solution for a number of different industries, including healthcare, 9-1-1 emergency, business, government, education, and more. </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">VRI provides a unique opportunity to connect with your clients and community on a more personal level than telephonic interpreting. </span><a href="http://telelanguage.com/services/video-remote-interpretation/"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Video Remote Interpretation Services</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> bridge the gap between over-the-phone interpreting and onsite interpreting, maintaining the personalization of an in-person experience and visual connection, but with the on-demand convenience of fast connect times and the highest level of accuracy.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Another bonus of using a Video Remote Interpreter is that is can be very budget-effective. A conventional on-site interpreter typically requires at least a two-hour minimum charge and possibly mileage and travel charges. A VRI will likely not have an hourly minimum or extra expenses associated.   </span>

&nbsp;
<h2>3 Key Benefits of Video Remote Interpreting</h2>
<ol>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;"><strong>Accuracy</strong> - The visual support associated with Video Remote Interpreting can provide enhanced accuracy for spoken language and American Sign Language (ASL). </span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;"><strong>Non-Verbal Communication</strong> - Seeing the facial expressions of the interpreter via VRI, and knowing they understood what was said and the ability to confirm the meaning of non-verbal communication can enhance the interpreting experience.</span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;"><strong>Immediacy and Connections</strong> - </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Video Remote Interpreting provides fast connect times for situations requiring immediate connections in which visual communication with the interpreter is necessary, or when a more personal connection will help the conversation.</span></li>
</ol>
<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-2795 aligncenter showimage" src="http://telelanguage.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/Infographic-Use-VRI.jpg" alt="Infographic-video-remote-interpreting" width="600" height="930" />

&nbsp;

<i><span style="font-weight: 400;">Telelanguage offers industry-certified interpreters across a number of industries. Our video remote interpreting service is </span></i><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">ASL-VRI is compliant with the Americans with Disabilities Act (ADA) and Section 504 of the Rehabilitation Act. We currently have a number of clients utilizing our Video Remote Interpreting service and we would be happy to answer any questions you have and help you determine in VRI is right for your company or service. Have questions? </span></i><a href="http://telelanguage.com/contact-us/"><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">Contact Telelanguage</span></i></a><i><span style="font-weight: 400;"> today! </span></i><i><span style="font-weight: 400;"> </span></i>

&nbsp;
<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Telelanguage offers 2000+ interpreters ready to speak in 250 languages!</span></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Call us today for a Free Demo at 888-983-5352 </span></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">Quality and expert interpretations are available telephonically, face to face, or video remote!</span></i></p>]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>When to Use Onsite Interpreters</title>
		<link>http://telelanguage.com/use-onsite-interpreters/</link>
		<pubDate>Wed, 16 Nov 2016 21:16:59 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[kimberlyscamman]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://telelanguage.com/?p=2865</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<h3>Wondering when to use onsite interpreters?</h3>
There's no doubt that when you're committed to providing excellent language services for your LEP clients that interpreters and translators are a necessity! The demand for qualified interpreters and translators is not slowing down anytime soon, but how do you know what type of <a href="http://telelanguage.com/services/">interpreter services</a> are appropriate? Should you use onsite interpreters, video remote interpreters, or telephonic interpreters? As a trusted language services provider for over 25 years, we help our clients determine what custom services will work best to serve their clients.
&nbsp;
<h3>Situations For Onsite Interpretation Services:</h3>
1.) Use onsite interpreters for lengthy appointments or interviews planned in advance.

2.) Use onsite interpreters if the conversation will be complex or time-consuming.

3.) If multiple patient appointments are being scheduled close to each other, it can be best to use an onsite interpreter.

4.) Accommodations for preference, i.e. if the Limited English Speaker prefers to have the interpreter onsite or feels uncomfortable using the telephone.

5.) If hand and body gestures are essential to get a message across, using onsite interpretation can be an essential service.

&nbsp;

<h4>(Video) When to Use Onsite Interpreters</h4>

<iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/fmUrB0S1Gqg?rel=0" width="560" height="315" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen" ></iframe>

&nbsp;
<h3>Use Certified Onsite Interpreters</h3>
It is important to offer the highest quality language services to get the right message across.

Telelanguage interpreters are the best professionally trained qualified and certified team in the industry. We have been developing and continuously modifying our interpreter training curriculum since 1991. We have involved leaders from healthcare industry as well as many other <a href="http://telelanguage.com/industries/">industries requiring language services</a> with our rigorous interpreter training and certification programs.

&nbsp;

<em>Whether for business, medical, legal and more, Telelanguage offers 2000+ industry certified interpreters in over 250 languages, and are available 24/7, 365 days a year. If you need help deciding what interpreter services are right for your clients, <a href="http://telelanguage.com/contact-us/">Contact us</a>. We're here to help you provide the highest quality language services for your clients and patients!</em>
<p style="text-align: center;">Call us today for a Free Demo at <span id="gc-number-0" class="gc-cs-link" title="Call with Google Voice">888-983-5352</span></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><i>Quality and expert interpretations are available telephonically, Onsite, or video remote!</i></p>
&nbsp;]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>How to Choose the Right Language Service Provider</title>
		<link>http://telelanguage.com/how-to-choose-language-service-provider/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 22 Nov 2016 20:31:18 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[kimberlyscamman]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://telelanguage.com/?p=2876</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[Choosing a language service provider and investing in a quality language access program is key to the success of many businesses and organizations. The need for interpreters and translators continues to rise and businesses are becoming more aware of the importance of providing the most effective communication for limited English proficient, non-English-speaking, Deaf, and Hard-of-Hearing clients and populations.

There are more than 37 million with reported hearing loss in the United States today and Census Bureau Reports have indicated at least <a href="http://www.census.gov/newsroom/press-releases/2015/cb15-185.html">350 Languages Spoken in U.S. Homes</a>.

<img src="http://telelanguage.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/language-service-provider-i.jpg" alt="Alt=&quot;language-service-provider-us-census" width="350" height="247" class="alignright size-full wp-image-2898" />We have previously written about <a href="http://telelanguage.com/why-certain-industries-need-to-provide-interpreter-services/">Top Industries that Require Interpreters and Translators</a>, but with the growing need for providing <strong>high-value language access programs</strong>, it's no longer a question of whether or not interpretation and translation services are necessary, but how can companies choose the RIGHT language service provider to fit their needs and the needs of their clients.
&nbsp;
<h3>4 Things to Consider When Choosing a Language Service Provider (LSP)</h3>
&nbsp;

<b>1.) The Language Service Provider Should Offer a Complete Language Access Solution</b>

Although your needs may center around a particular service, i.e. Telephonic
Interpretation for Customer Service, it’s important to consider whether the LSP is able to accommodate situations that may arise requiring additional services such as: Onsite Interpretation (face-to-face interpretation), Video Remote Interpretation, or Document Translation.
&nbsp;
<b>2.) Your LSP Should Be Familiar with the Needs of Your Industry</b>

If your business centers around medical or healthcare, you wouldn’t want to consider an LSP that had no experience in that industry, right? Check the <a href="http://telelanguage.com/industries/">industries supported by your language service provider</a> to ensure they will be able to support the needs of your industry (including any special terminology and ethics).
&nbsp;
<b>3.) Choose a Language Service Provider with High Standard for Interpreters and Translators</b>

Throughout the United States, Interpreters are key and highly-valued members of the language community. With growing need and demands, their responsibilities have also evolved greatly. Be sure to inquire about the testing of interpreters and translators and that training meets or exceeds industry standards.
&nbsp;
<b>4.) Your Language Service Provider should offer languages to cover the diversity of languages spoken.</b>

Choosing an LSP that offers multiple languages to grow with the needs of your company is key for success in any industry. Ask Language Service Providers about the languages they offer to be sure it will suit your needs.
&nbsp;
Armed with these 4 questions, you will be well-equipped to choose an excellent language service provider to help take your language services to the next level. Have any tips for choosing an LSP or effectively using interpreters and translators you’d like us to know? Be sure to share them in the comments below!
&nbsp;
<i>Telelanguage has been a trusted language service provider for over 25 years! We offer a complete package of language services to fit your needs, including; Onsite Interpretation, Over-the-Phone Interpretation, Video Remote Interpretation and Document Translation. We service multiple industries and have <a href="http://telelanguage.com/resources/interpreter-certification/">rigorous training and certification programs for interpreters</a> that far exceed industry standards. Our 2000+ certified interpreters are ready to speak in over 250 languages with dedicated support 24/7/365. If you are looking for a reliable language service provider or thinking about switching, <a href="http://telelanguage.com/contact-us/">contact us</a> for more information, or a free demo. We’d love to help you provide the language access program you need.</i>
&nbsp;
<center>Telelanguage offers 2000+ interpreters ready to speak in 250 languages!
Call us today for a Free Demo at 888-983-5352
Quality and expert interpretations are available telephonically, face to face, and video remote!</center>]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>Free CE Webinar for Interpreters (CCHI)</title>
		<link>http://telelanguage.com/free-ce-webinar-for-interpreters-cchi/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 29 Nov 2016 20:37:31 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[kimberlyscamman]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://telelanguage.com/?p=2905</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<h2>Certification Commission for Healthcare Interpreters (CCHI) Presents Free CE Webinar for Interpreters on December, 7th, 2016.</h2>
There’s no doubt that language interpreters play a key role in our society, helping to provide understanding and effective communication in numerous industries, such as Healthcare and Medical, 9-1-1 Emergency, Legal and Business. With the ever changing landscape of the language industry and the rising need for language access programs, it is more important than ever than interpreters stay at the top of their game! This means that in addition to rigorous testing and training for <a href="http://telelanguage.com/resources/interpreter-certification/" target="_blank">interpreter certification programs</a>, interpreters must also constantly be training and participating in continuing education for interpreters to be able to provide the highest level of language services.

To help certified interpreters in their continuing education, we would like to recommend this <strong>free CE webinar for interpreters</strong>, <em>Interpreting the Psychiatric Interview: How Language Affects the Mental Status Exam,</em> presented by <a href="http://www.cchicertification.org/index.php" target="_blank">Certification Commission for Healthcare Interpreters (CCHI)</a>, and will be for interpreters of ALL languages.

This webinar is accredited by CEAP/CCHI for 1.5 CE hours and will be the last CE course of this year (2016).

&nbsp;
<h3>About CCHI</h3>
<img class="alignleft wp-image-2920 size-full" src="http://telelanguage.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/ceap-e1480450919574.jpg" alt="Alt=&quot;CEAP Logo for CE Webinar for Interpreters&quot;" width="200" height="74" />Founded in 2009, CCHI is a 501(c)(6) organization, and was the first organization certifying healthcare interpreters to receive NCCA accreditation. CCHI’s mission is “to develop and direct a comprehensive credentialing program for healthcare interpreters, bring together representatives from national and regional non-profit interpreting associations, language companies, community-based organizations, educational institutions, healthcare providers, and advocates for LEP individuals.”

&nbsp;
<h3>About the Webinar</h3>
<i>(Via the CCHI CEAP Team)</i>

To help you deepen your knowledge about mental health interpreting and to meet the renewal requirements if you are certified, we are excited to offer this free Continuing Education webinar for interpreters of any language. This is our last CE webinar in 2016.

<a href="https://attendee.gotowebinar.com/registration/full.tmpl?HasEmail=false&amp;webinar=8281075557531011585"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-2917" src="http://telelanguage.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/ce4terps.jpg" alt="Alt=&quot;Free CE Webinar for Interpreters&quot;" width="400" height="385" /></a>

Space is limited! Keep in mind that in order to receive certificates of attendance, you must connect to the webinar via computer (VoIP) and not only via a phone,and participate in all activities as directed by the presenter at the time of the live webinar. The certificates and materials used during the webinar will be emailed to participants within two weeks of the event. Please make sure to mark your calendar for your own time zone and connect 5-10 minutes before the webinar start time. If you have any audio or video issues during the webinar, please contact the <a href="https://care.citrixonline.com/gotowebinar" target="_blank">GoToWebinar Customer Support</a> directly.

&nbsp;

<strong>Webinar #6. December 7, 2016 at 3 pm ET/ 2 pm CT/ 1 pm MT/ 12 pm PT</strong>

<strong>Interpreting the Psychiatric Interview: How Language Affects the Mental Status Exam</strong>

<strong>To register go to: </strong>  <a href="https://attendee.gotowebinar.com/register/8281075557531011585">https://attendee.gotowebinar.com/register/8281075557531011585</a>

&nbsp;

Interpreting a psychiatric interview poses unique challenges. The entire interview serves as a mental status exam and providers have specific reasons to ask questions in a certain way. An interpreter who is ill-equipped to deal with these challenges can unknowingly cloud the provider’s ability to assess the patient correctly.
CCHI has invited Maria Carla Faccini, CHI™-Spanish, and Dr. Adrienne D. Mishkin to present this free, language-neutral, Continuing Education webinar “Interpreting the Psychiatric Interview: How Language Affects the Mental Status Exam” so that attendees can learn about the provider’s thought process and some of the techniques they use to interview patients. The speakers will also discuss examples that show how a skilled interpreter can improve the quality of the interview. Strategies that the interpreter can use to overcome challenges typical for this appointment type will also be discussed.

<strong>This webinar is accredited by CEAP/CCHI for 1.5 CE hours and is intended for intermediate-level interpreters.</strong>

&nbsp;
<h3>Meet Your Presenters:</h3>
<b><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-2918" src="http://telelanguage.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/maria-carlie.jpg" alt="Alt=&quot;Maria Carla Faccini&quot; " width="99" height="100" />Maria Carla Faccini</b> has been certified as a health care interpreter by the Certification Commission for Healthcare Interpreters. She has an MA in conference interpreting (Spanish-English-French) from the Middlebury Institute of International Studies at Monterey and a bachelor’s degree in education from the Universidad del Zulia in Maracaibo, Venezuela. She works as a medical interpreter/translator at Stanford Health Care and is also a freelance interpreter. She has 12 years of experience interpreting in medical settings in New York and California. She has been training medical interpreters since 2003.

<b><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-2919" src="http://telelanguage.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/adrieene.jpg" alt="Alt=&quot;Dr Adrienne D. Mishkin&quot;" width="87" height="100" />Dr. Adrienne D. Mishkin</b> is a board-certified psychiatrist with a specialization in psychosomaticmedicine. She has a master’s degree in public health from the Tulane University School of Medicine, where she completed her medical training. After receiving her degree from Tulane, she completed psychiatric training at St. Luke’s-Roosevelt Hospital Center, followed by a psychosomatic fellowship at Montefiore Hospital. She is currently the psychiatric liaison to the blood and marrow transplantation program at Columbia University Medical Center/New York Presbyterian Hospital. She is also enrolled in a bioethics master’s degree program at Yeshiva University.

&nbsp;
<h3>See You There!</h3>
Be sure to check in and follow updates from CCHI and the webinar on social media using the CCHI hashtag #CE4terps on Facebook, Twitter, and LinkedIn.

With 25 years experience providing language interpretation services for the healthcare industry, we know how important training and education is for interpreters. Telelanguage would encourage all certified interpreters to take advantage of this free CE webinar for interpreters.

We’ll see you at the webinar!

&nbsp;

<em>Our Telelanguage Interpreter Certification Program (TICP) is a 120-hour training course combined with a 370-page training manual, exceeding the industry standard 30-hour training. In addition to TICP training, Telelanguage also provides a medical interpreter certification, requiring 120 Hours of Academic Medical Training &amp; Healthcare Interpreting Ethics, which is well above the National Board of Medical Interpreters Requirements. If you have questions about our Certification Program or Interpreter Service, please don’t hesitate to <a href="http://telelanguage.com/contact-us/" target="_blank">contact Telelanguage</a> today!</em>

&nbsp;

	<item>
		<title>The Importance of Certified Medical Interpreters in Hospitals</title>
		<link>http://telelanguage.com/certified-medical-interpreters-in-hospitals/</link>
		<pubDate>Wed, 07 Dec 2016 16:31:28 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[kimberlyscamman]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://telelanguage.com/?p=3050</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p style="text-align: left;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Certified medical interpreters in hospitals are a valuable part of the medical community. In any professional setting, effective communication is key, but in hospital and emergency situation, where being understood can be life or death, language access is critical. </span></p>
<span style="font-weight: 400;">New updates to the Affordable Care Act (Section 1557) prompted us to write</span> <a href="http://telelanguage.com/qualified-interpreter-section-1557/"><span style="font-weight: 400;">How Can Healthcare Providers Provide a Qualified Interpreter for LEP Patients?</span></a>

<span style="font-weight: 400;"> As a trusted service language service provider for 25+ years, Telelanguage knows the importance of having certified medical interpreters in hospitals and medical settings.   </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Hospitals that receive federal funding, including Medicare and Medicaid, must provide culturally and linguistically appropriate services, and qualified interpreters. </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Many hospital administrators often feel burdened by the expense of a great language access program, but the truth is having these services save time, money, resources and, yes, lives.</span>
<h2>5 Reasons to Have Certified Medical Interpreters in Hospitals</h2>
<a href="https://www.federalregister.gov/documents/2016/05/18/2016-11458/nondiscrimination-in-health-programs-and-activities"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Limited English Proficiency</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> characterizes any individual “whose primary language for communication is </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">not English” and “is considered an <a href="http://telelanguage.com/contact-us/"><img class="alignleft wp-image-2785 size-full" src="http://telelanguage.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/1557compliance.png" alt="Alt=&quot;Medical Interpreters in hospitals_Low Rates Section 1557&quot;" width="250" height="156" /></a>individual with limited English proficiency if the individual has a limited ability to read, write, speak or understand English.” Medical interpreters help provide effective communication for Limited English Proficient (LEP) patients and clients.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">1.) The U.S. Census Bureau Reports at Least</span> <a href="http://www.census.gov/newsroom/press-releases/2015/cb15-185.html"><span style="font-weight: 400;">350 Languages Spoken in U.S. Homes</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">.</span></a>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">2.)</span> <a href="http://www.migrationpolicy.org/article/limited-english-proficient-population-united-states"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Immigrants to the United States</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> come from many different language backgrounds and may be in various stages of English proficiency. Of the total immigrant population of 41.3 million in 2013, about half was LEP.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">3.) Implementing language access programs and using certified interpreters in hospitals can reduce waste represented by overtreatment and medical errors. </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">4.) Research suggests that LEP patients are more likely than English-speaking (ES) patients to experience </span><a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5111827/"><span style="font-weight: 400;">safety events caused by communication errors</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">5.) Title VI of the Civil Rights Act:</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">“No person in the United States shall on the ground of race, color or national origin, be excluded from participation in, be denied the benefits of, or be subjected to discrimination under any program or activity receiving Federal financial assistance”</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Using certified medical interpreters in hospitals has never been so important, and with the number of LEP individuals rising in the United States, it is imperative that hospitals implement great language access programs now. </span>

<em><span style="font-weight: 400;">Telelanguage has over 2000 interpreters ready to communicate in 250 languages. Our </span><a href="http://telelanguage.com/industries/healthcare/"><span style="font-weight: 400;">team of certified medical interpreters</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> is an integral and respected part of the medical community. We know making changes isn’t alway easy, that’s why we offer special low rates for Section 1557 Compliance. If you need help with compliance, please </span><a href="http://telelanguage.com/contact-us/"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Contact Us for more information</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">.</span></em>

&nbsp;
<p style="text-align: center;">Certified medical interpreters ready to speak in 200 languages!</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">Call Telelanguage today at <a href="tel:1-888-983-5352">1-888-983-5352</a></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">Quality and expert interpretations for your medical appointments telephonically, face to face, or video remote!</p>]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>When to Use Legal Interpreters (Common Settings)</title>
		<link>http://telelanguage.com/common-situtations-legal-interpreters/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 13 Dec 2016 20:58:11 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[kimberlyscamman]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://telelanguage.com/?p=3125</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<span style="font-weight: 400;">Telelanguage is a language services company and we have been providing <a href="http://telelanguage.com/industries/legal-and-judicial/">legal and judicial interpreting services</a> since 1991. Legal settings require the highest level of accuracy and attention to detail. It is important that legal interpreters have more than just fluency, but extensive knowledge of legal terminology and protocol.</span>

As of 2013, more than 20 percent of individuals living in the United States <a href="http://www.lsc.gov/grants-grantee-resources/resources-topic-type/language-access-cultural-sensitivity" target="_blank">speak a language other than English in their home</a>.

<span style="font-weight: 400;">With a growing number of limited English proficient (LEP) individuals nationwide, interpreters have become a valuable part of the legal community. So how do legal interpreters help? Here are 9 common situations where a legal interpreter may be needed:  </span>

<b>Common Situations for Legal Interpreters:</b>
<ol>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Depositions<a href="http://telelanguage.com/industries/legal-and-judicial/"><img class="alignright size-full wp-image-3129" src="http://telelanguage.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/12/in-person-interpreting.jpeg" alt="Alt=&quot;Legal interpreters meeting&quot;" width="276" height="183" /></a> </span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Hearings</span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Trials</span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Examinations</span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Consultations</span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Arbitration and Mediation</span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Judicial proceedings</span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Independent Medical Examinations (IMEs)</span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Legal Conferences</span></li>
</ol>
<span style="font-weight: 400;">In addition to legal terminology and protocol, <strong>legal interpreters </strong>may also specialize in a particular area of law, such as immigration law, family law, workers’ comp, etc.  Choosing an industry certified legal interpreter will ensure proper privacy and the most accurate legal interpreting services.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">When a language barrier arises in a legal setting, using certified legal interpreters and translators will ensure that individuals with limited English proficiency will be served at the highest level of accuracy. Understanding and efficient communication are vital in legal settings, be it a deposition, client meeting, legal document translation, or judicial proceeding.  </span>

&nbsp;

<i><span style="font-weight: 400;">Telelanguage provides legal interpreting services and legal translation services in 250 languages. Security and confidentiality are extremely important to us. We provide a privacy notice to our customers who utilize our telephonic and face-to-face interpretation services. We protect personal and confidential information encountered during the interpretation process by maintaining physical, electronic, and procedural safeguards that meet or exceed applicable law. </span></i>

<i><span style="font-weight: 400;">If you are looking for a reliable language service provider or thinking about switching, </span></i><a href="http://telelanguage.com/contact-us/"><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">contact us</span></i></a><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">  for more information, or a free demo. </span></i>
<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Telelanguage offers 2000+ interpreters ready to speak in 250 languages!</span></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Call us today for a Free Demo at </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">888-983-5352</span></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">Legal interpreters are available telephonically, face to face, and video remote!</span></i></p>]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>Importance of Scheduling Software for Language Service Providers</title>
		<link>http://telelanguage.com/scheduling-software-for-language-service-providers/</link>
		<pubDate>Thu, 22 Dec 2016 20:41:34 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[kimberlyscamman]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://telelanguage.com/?p=3131</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<span style="font-weight: 400;">The language service industry is growing at a rapid pace. Whether you are a language services agency, hospital, or international business, the number of people in need of language services is increasing. The 2015 Census Bureau Reports at Least </span><a href="http://www.census.gov/newsroom/press-releases/2015/cb15-185.html"><span style="font-weight: 400;">350 Languages Spoken in U.S. Homes</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">. But with the growing Limited English Proficient (LEP) population, how can you provide high-quality language services, and keep up with increased interpreter requests?</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Interpreting management is a time-consuming task. As a leader in </span><a href="http://www.telelanguage.com"><span style="font-weight: 400;">interpretation and translation services</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> for over 20 years, we believe the implementation of a robust </span><b>software for language service providers</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> can help providers grow by cutting down on the time and resources spent on management so you can focus on providing excellent language services.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Telelanguage’s </span><a href="http://telelanguage.com/services/scheduling-software/"><span style="font-weight: 400;">interpreter scheduling software</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">, The Global Interpreter Platform (GIP), </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">is a software for language service providers to manage face-to-face interpretation requests, invoicing clients, paying interpreters and reporting. GIP was designed for interpreter service providers of all sizes and built for multiple industries.</span>

[caption id="attachment_3139" align="aligncenter" width="530"]<a href="http://telelanguage.com/services/scheduling-software/"><img class="wp-image-3139 size-full" src="http://telelanguage.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/12/GIP.jpg" alt="Alt:&quot;GIP Software for Language Service Providers&quot;" width="530" height="323" /></a> Global Interpreter Platform (GIP): Complete Interpreter Scheduling Software[/caption]
&nbsp;
<h2>Here are our 6 easy steps to using your interpreter management software, the GIP:</h2>
&nbsp;
<h3>Step 1: Getting Started</h3>
<span style="font-weight: 400;">Request a </span><a href="http://telelanguage.com/contact-us/"><span style="font-weight: 400;">free demo</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> of our interpreter scheduling software or select the package that fits your company needs. We will email you your login ID and Password. </span>
<h3>Step 2: Login</h3>
<span style="font-weight: 400;">You complete interpreter scheduling software is ready to use for your business. Just login using your credentials and enter your customers and interpreters or download it using Excel.</span>
<h3>Step 3: Customize It</h3>
<span style="font-weight: 400;">Customize the look and feel of the interpreter scheduling software with your company branding, logo, forms and messaging.</span>
<h3>Step 4: Managing Language Services</h3>
<span style="font-weight: 400;">Your customers can enter interpreter requests online and interpreters manage their schedules and appointments using your company ISS.</span>
<h3>Step 5: Access From Anywhere</h3>
<span style="font-weight: 400;">Monitor how interpreter requests are entered and get assigned to interpreters without time-consuming and unnecessary staff involvement. Make scheduling adjustments as needed.</span>
<h3>Step 6: Invoice Customers and Pay Interpreters</h3>
<span style="font-weight: 400;">Easily create invoices to your customers and payment logs to your interpreters based on the complete history of each assignment, including customer signed order forms.</span>
<h3>Step 7: Get the Support You Need</h3>
<span style="font-weight: 400;">24/7 technical support is available in our GIP plans. A dedicated IT staff is available around the clock to assist you. Our team of trainers, programmers, and developers all work together to provide efficient support when you need it.</span>

&nbsp;

<span style="font-weight: 400;">With the increased demand for interpreters on the rise, having an all-inclusive software for language service providers like the Global Interpreter Platform can help your company put time and resources into the right places to grow effectively and continue to provide high-quality language services. </span>

<em><span style="font-weight: 400;">Have questions about our complete interpreter scheduling software? </span><a href="http://telelanguage.com/contact-us/"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Contact us</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> for more information, or to schedule you free GIP demo! </span></em>
<h3 style="text-align: center;"><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">The Global Interpreter Platform (GIP)</span></i></h3>
<h3 style="text-align: center;"><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">14 Day FREE Trial – Schedule a Demo Today!</span></i></h3>
<p style="text-align: center;"><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">Call Telelanguage For More Info: 888.983.5352</span></i></p>

<h3 style="text-align: center;"></h3>]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>Language Services Industry: 8 Things You Should Know (Infographic)</title>
		<link>http://telelanguage.com/infographic-language-services-industry/</link>
		<pubDate>Wed, 28 Dec 2016 21:10:05 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[kimberlyscamman]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://telelanguage.com/?p=3145</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<span style="font-weight: 400;">The language services industry has never been more important and relevant than it is now, and that trend continues to grow. Whether you’re a language service provider, an interpreter, or an international company, it’s important to recognize your contribution to a growing industry and the need for quality globalization, localization and interpreter services within the </span><a href="http://www.telelanguage.com"><span style="font-weight: 400;">language services</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> industry.</span>

&nbsp;

<span style="font-weight: 400;">The infographic below highlights 8 things you should know about the language services industry: </span>
<ol>
&nbsp;
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">The size of the overall global language industry in 2016 is estimated at $40 Billion (USD), with estimates of up to $45 Billion by 2020. </span><span style="font-weight: 400;"><a href="https://www.gala-global.org/industry/industry-facts-and-data#fn2 [1]">GALA (Globalization and Localization Association)</a> </span></li>
&nbsp;
 	<li>Common Sense Advisory Research (CSA Research) shows an annual <a href="http://content.lionbridge.com/lionbridge-named-top-ranked-language-service-provider-2015/"><span style="font-weight: 400;">growth rate of 6.46%</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> for the language services market. </span></li>
&nbsp;
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">I</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">nc. Magazine lists the language industry as one of the </span><a href="http://www.inc.com/magazine/201404/darren-dahl/the-best-industries-for-starting-a-business.html"><span style="font-weight: 400;">top industries for starting a business</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">.</span></li>
&nbsp;
 	<li>Localization is the 4th fastest-growing industry in the United States.</li>
&nbsp;
 	<li>Revenues from digital English language learning products in Asia are projected to nearly double from 2013 (US$863.1 million) to US$1.6 billion by 2018. <span style="font-weight: 400;"><a href="http://monitor.icef.com/2014/05/surging-global-demand-for-digital-language-learning/">ICEF Monitor</a></span></li>
&nbsp;
 	<li>Outsourcing is the preferred method for managing language services for domestic, multicultural, or global use. (Full-service LSPs or freelancers.)</li>
&nbsp;
 	<li>The number of <a href="http://monitor.icef.com/2016/11/one-million-international-students-us/"><span style="font-weight: 400;">foreign students in the US</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> has surpassed the one million mark to reach 1,043,839.</span></li>
&nbsp;
 	<li>The United States Census Bureau Reports at Least 350 <a href="http://www.census.gov/newsroom/press-releases/2015/cb15-185.html"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Languages Spoken in U.S. Homes</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">.</span></li>
</ol>
&nbsp;

<img class="aligncenter wp-image-3147 size-large" src="http://telelanguage.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/12/Infographic_8-things-langua-538x1024.jpg" alt="Alt=&quot;Infographic: Language Services Industry&quot;" width="538" height="1024" />

&nbsp;

<i><span style="font-weight: 400;">The language services industry continues to grow and Telelanguage is proud to have been at the forefront of interpreter services across all industries since 1991. Whether you're looking for an interpreter for your next meeting or ready to up your language services game for your clients, Telelanguage is here to answer your questions and help you get started. </span></i><a href="http://telelanguage.com/contact-us/"><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">Contact Us</span></i></a><i><span style="font-weight: 400;"> for more information. </span></i>

&nbsp;
<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Certified interpreters ready to speak in 200 languages!</span></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Call us today at </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">888-983-5352</span></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">Quality interpreter services are available telephonically, face to face, or by video remote!</span></i></p>

	<item>
		<title>Top 10 Foreign Languages Spoken in the United States</title>
		<link>http://telelanguage.com/top-10-foreign-languages-spoken-in-the-united-states/</link>
		<pubDate>Thu, 05 Jan 2017 18:37:51 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[kimberlyscamman]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://telelanguage.com/?p=3159</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[We hear many foreign languages every day. The United States draws persons from many countries around the world, many of whom speak foreign languages. The diversity of languages in the United States may be surprising to most, as a 2015 Census Bureau Reported at Least 350 Languages Spoken in U.S. Homes.

In 2013, there were approximately 25.1 million individuals considered Limited English Proficient who spoke a language other than English at home. The Limited English Proficient, or LEP, population <a href="http://www.migrationpolicy.org/article/limited-english-proficient-population-united-states" target="_blank">represented 8% of the total U.S. population</a> over the age of 5. Some U.S. cities, like New York, Miami and Los Angeles have <a href="http://telelanguage.com/interpretation-translation-locations/" target="_blank">higher immigrant and LEP populations</a>:

A 2011 U.S. Census Bureau report identified these 10 foreign languages as the most popular in the United States.

&nbsp;

<h2>Top 10 Foreign Languages Spoken in the United States</h2>

&nbsp;
<iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/uKgANoUYvjQ?rel=0" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>
&nbsp;

<strong>10) Italian</strong>
Italian Speakers in the United States: 723,632 (Represents a nearly 50% decline from 1980.) Popular United States Locations: New York, Boston, Chicago, Philadelphia
&nbsp;
<strong>9) Russian</strong>
Russian Speakers in the United States: 905,843 (Represents 391% increase from 1980.)
Popular United States Locations: New York, Los Angeles, Chicago, San Francisco
&nbsp;
<strong>8) Arabic</strong>
Arabic Speakers in the United States: 951,699 (Represents approximately 3.5x increase from 1980.)
Popular United States Locations: Michigan, Los Angeles, San Francisco, Washington D.C.
&nbsp;
<strong>7) Korean</strong>
Korean Speakers in the United States: 1,141,277 (Represents approximately 4x increase from 1980.)
Popular United States Locations: Los Angeles, New York, Chicago, Washington D.C.
&nbsp;
<strong>6) German</strong>
German Speakers in the United States: 1,083,637 (Represents 30% decrease from 1980.)
Popular United States Locations: New York, Chicago, Los Angeles and Washington DC
&nbsp;
<strong>5) French</strong>
French Speakers in the United States: 1,301,443 (Represents 28% increase from 1980.)
Popular United States Locations: New York, Washington D.C., Miami, Boston
&nbsp;
<strong>4) Vietnamese</strong>
Vietnamese Speakers in the United States: 1,419,539 (510% increase from 1980.)
Popular United States Locations: Los Angeles, San Jose, Dallas, Houston
&nbsp;
<strong>3) Tagalog</strong>
Tagalog Speakers in the United States:1,594,413 (Represents 3x increase from 1980.)
Popular United States Locations: Los Angeles, New York, San Francisco, San Diego
&nbsp;
<strong>2) Chinese</strong>
Chinese Speakers in the United States: 2,882,497 (Represents 290% increase from 1980.) Popular United States Locations: New York, Los Angeles, San Francisco
&nbsp;
<strong>1) Spanish</strong>
Spanish Speakers in the United States: 37,579,787 (Represents 210% increase from 1980.) Popular United States Locations: Los Angeles, New York, Chicago, Miami
&nbsp;
With the diversity of foreign languages in the United States growing and rising LEP populations, interpreters and translators are extremely important. From <a href="http://telelanguage.com/industries/healthcare/" target="_blank">medical interpreting</a> to legal interpreting, business to everyday situations, an interpreter’s job helps to achieve effective communication and understanding.

<em>Telelanguage has provided quality interpretation services since 1991 in 250 languages. Have questions about interpreter services? <a href="http://telelanguage.com/contact-us/" target="_blank">Contact us</a> and we would be happy to answer any questions you have.</em>

&nbsp;
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Certified interpreters ready to speak in 200 languages!</strong>
Call us today at 888-983-5352
Quality interpreter services are available telephonically, face to face, or by video remote!</p>]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>Language Services and the Healthcare Industry in 2017</title>
		<link>http://telelanguage.com/language-services-healthcare-2017/</link>
		<pubDate>Fri, 13 Jan 2017 09:00:52 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[kimberlyscamman]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://telelanguage.com/?p=3169</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[2016 saw considerable changes to regulations for hospitals and the healthcare industry. These changes highlight the need for effective language services and language access programs in hospitals and health care settings. Implementation of higher quality language access programs will continue to be a priority for the healthcare industry in 2017.

<a href="http://telelanguage.com/contact-us/" target="_blank"><img class="alignleft wp-image-2785" src="http://telelanguage.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/1557compliance.png" alt="Alt=&quot;Medical Interpreters in hospitals_Low Rates Section 1557&quot;" width="200" height="125" /></a>One major change for the healthcare industry in 2016 was the <a href="http://telelanguage.com/qualified-interpreter-section-1557/" target="_blank">Section 1557 ruling by Health and Human Services (HHS)</a>. This new ruling elevates the level of language access that hospitals and government funded healthcare programs must offer Limited English Proficient (LEP) patients and also changed the language of who may be considered an interpreter from “Competent" to “Qualified." The ruling mandated compliance by October 18th, 2016.

Another important change was the <i>Overall Hospital Quality Star Rating System </i>from the <a href="https://www.cms.gov/Newsroom/MediaReleaseDatabase/Fact-sheets/2016-Fact-sheets-items/2016-07-27.html">Center for Medicare and Medicaid Services (CMS)</a> (July 2016). The new rating system assigns United States hospitals a one-to-five star rating. With the need for more quality language access programs in hospitals, improving these language access programs will remain a major focus for hospitals and healthcare programs.

As a well-known leader in promoting <strong>affordable access to health care interpretation quality</strong>, Telelanguage released their “National Health Law Program and Affordable Healthcare Act: Language Access Checklist,” ensuring special low rates for <strong>Section 1557 compliance</strong>. As a top provider of interpreter services, Telelanguage believes that all healthcare organizations should have affordable access to the best-qualified language service support.

&nbsp;
<p style="text-align: center;">[<a href="http://telelanguage.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/Telelanguage-supports-new-National-Health-Law.pdf" target="_blank">DOWNLOAD</a> the Language Access Checklist.]</p>

[caption id="attachment_3172" align="aligncenter" width="769"]<a href="http://telelanguage.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/Telelanguage-supports-new-National-Health-Law.pdf"><img class="size-full wp-image-3172" src="http://telelanguage.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Health-care-act.png" alt="Alt=&quot;Language Access Checklist: Language Services&quot;" width="769" height="423" /></a> [Free Download] The National Health Law Program and Affordable Healthcare Act: Language Access Checklist.[/caption]&nbsp;

Telelanguage made <a href="http://telelanguage.com/services/video-remote-interpretation/">Video Remote Interpreting (VRI)</a>, a video telecommunication service, available to their customers. Providing state-of-the-art VRI technology to round out our interpretation services has proven to be an integral component of language service plans, helping to bridge the gap between telephonic interpretation and onsite interpretation. VRI is a unique opportunity for language service providers to connect with their clients and community, offering more visual support.

We made changes to the Telelanguage website in 2016 to make it even more user-friendly, and in 2017, we will be adding new Free Support Materials to better serve our clients and help them take their language services to new heights!

Language access programs and effective language services will continue to dominate in 2017, and Telelanguage is committed to providing the most comprehensive language services and cutting-edge technologies to support interpretation needs. Our interpreters are industry-certified, and our <a href="http://telelanguage.com/resources/interpreter-certification/" target="_blank">National Interpreter Certification Program (TCIP)</a> provides rigorous training that exceeds national standards.

<em>
Looking to provide more quality language services in 2017? <a href="http://telelanguage.com/contact-us/">Contact Telelanguage</a> today for a free consultation. We look forward to providing you with the highest quality language services that we have been providing our customers for over 25 years.</em>
<i>
</i>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Certified medical interpreters ready to speak in 250 languages!</em>
<em>Call Telelanguage today at <a href="tel:1-888-983-5352">1-888-983-5352</a></em></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Quality and expert interpretations for your medical appointments</em>
<em>telephonically, face to face, or via video remote!</em></p>]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>Improving Hospital Language Services is a Win for Everyone</title>
		<link>http://telelanguage.com/improving-hospital-language-services/</link>
		<pubDate>Fri, 20 Jan 2017 20:27:56 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[kimberlyscamman]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://telelanguage.com/?p=3187</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<span style="font-weight: 400;">As Limited English Proficiency in the United States continues to rise, and the LEP population </span><a href="http://www.migrationpolicy.org/article/limited-english-proficient-population-united-states"><span style="font-weight: 400;">over 25 million</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">, interpreters and translators have become a key part of many major industries, such as legal and judicial, hospitality, social services and of course, healthcare. The </span><a href="http://telelanguage.com/language-services-healthcare-2017/"><span style="font-weight: 400;">changes for the healthcare industry</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> in 2016 have made Hospital language services a top priority.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Medical Interpreters allow for effective communication between hospital staff and LEP patients. Communication is vital in hospital situations for hospital staff to offer the appropriate care and ensure that all information about care is understood by the patient.</span> &nbsp;
&nbsp;

<b>4 Ways Improving Hospital Language Services is a Win for Everyone:</b>
<ol>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Medical interpreters enable direct communication between providers and LEP patients, ensuring that patients receive accurate information about diagnosis and care. Professional interpreters help hospital language services by assisting in each step of the healthcare process.</span></li> &nbsp;
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Language Barriers may lead to communication problems, which increases the risk of patient safety events. Research suggests that LEP patients are more likely than English-speaking (ES) patients to experience safety events caused by communication errors. The </span><a href="https://www.ahrq.gov/professionals/systems/hospital/lepguide/lepguide1.html#fig2"><span style="font-weight: 400;">root causes of patient safety events</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> for LEP patients are related to communication and lack of use of qualified medical interpreters. Qualified interpreters, or as we recommend, </span><a href="http://telelanguage.com/industries/healthcare/"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Certified Medical Interpreters</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">, have experience interpreting as well as an understanding of medical terminology.</span></li> &nbsp;
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Qualified interpreters may impact </span><a href="http://www.hcahpsonline.org/home.aspx"><span style="font-weight: 400;">HCAHPS scores</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">. Effective hospital language services can increase overall patient satisfaction.  Of the nine key topics, communication and information are important factors that affect ratings: communication with doctors, communication with nurses, responsiveness of hospital staff, pain management, communication about medicines, discharge information, cleanliness of the hospital environment, quietness of the hospital environment, and transition of care.</span></li> &nbsp;
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Appropriate hospital language services can increase customer support satisfaction. </span><a href="http://www.icmi.com/~/media/Multilanguage-Customer-Support-Research-Report.ashx"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Research confirms</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> that language services can improve customer support satisfaction by 72%, and increase brand loyalty by 58%.</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span></li>
</ol> &nbsp;
<span style="font-weight: 400;">The United States foreign-born population is set to double by 2050, and the number of Non-English-Speaking and LEP patients requiring hospital language services is going to continue to rise. It is imperative that hospitals continue to implement the best language services to ensure patient safety, increase patient satisfaction, and reach overall goals. </span> &nbsp;
&nbsp;
<i><span style="font-weight: 400;">Telelanguage has been a leading provider of hospital language services since 1991, and we believe that all healthcare organizations should have affordable access to the best-qualified language service support. Ask us about </span></i><a href="http://telelanguage.com/contact-us/"><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">Special Low Rates for Section 1557 Compliance</span></i></a><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">. 
&nbsp; </span></i>
<p style="text-align: center;"><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">Certified medical interpreters ready to speak in 250 languages!</span></i></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">Call Telelanguage today at </span></i><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">1-888-983-5352</span></i></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">Expert interpretations for medical appointments telephonically, face to face, or via video remote!</span></i></p>
]]></content:encoded>
